<TEXT>
president bush won democratic praise wednesday 
night for his plan to cut us and soviet forces in central europe 
while senate gop leader bob dole said the proposal would put the 
united states on the offensive at the bargaining table 
rep les aspin the democratic chairman of the house armed 
services committee said the president should be congratulated 
for the plan outlined in a state of the union address 
trying to negotiate lower limits on forces deployed in europe 
is clearly a good idea said the wisconsin democrat 
said dole the ball is now in soviet leader mikhail 
gorbachevs court 
at the same time they were hailing his troop cut proposal 
democrats made plain their intention to battle with bush over other 
issues in the current electionyear session of congress 
in a nationally televised speech that served as the formal 
democratic response house speaker thomas s foley said his party 
would work with the president wherever and whenever we can on 
some issues we will have difference because we care deeply about 
certain principles he said 
he scoffed at bushs call for a meager 2 percent rise in 
education spending and said democrats would battle the 
administration this year on legislation dealing with capital gains 
taxes child care and clean air as for abortion he said we 
will continue to defend a womans right to choose for we are 
convinced that politicians cannot and should not attempt to make 
the choice 
house democratic leader richard gephardt of missouri faulted 
bush for not being more specific about how he intends to 
strengthen our economy and lift the economic fortunes of people who 
work for a living 
republicans applauded bushs statement that the last thing we 
need to do is mess around with social security with gop house 
whip newt gingrich of georgia saying the presidents position is 
going to be clearly the only acceptable political position saying 
that nothing affecting benefits can be considered 
sen daniel patrick moynihan dny in an attempt to block the 
government from using surplus social security taxes has proposed 
rolling back a tax increase that took effect jan 1 and to reduce 
another increase scheduled for next year 
following the speech moynihan said despite bushs promise not 
to fool with social security theyre messing around with social 
security where theyre using the trust fund as general revenue 
overall dole called bushs speech an optimistic can do 
state of the union which advances a hope agenda one in sharp 
contrast with the democrats nope agenda 
but house democratic whip william gray dpa said bushs 
speech ought to be introduced to his budget theres a 
disconnect 
but domestic issues aside lawmakers on both sides of the aisle 
chorused their praise of bushs proposal to reduce troops in the 
socalled central front in europe to 195000 for each 
superpower 
sen john warner of virginia ranking republican on the senate 
armed services committee said bush skillfully seized the element 
of surprise and thereby seized the opportunity to put the united 
states back into the forefront of negotiations to reduce 
conventional forces 
sen sam nunn dga the chairman of the senate armed services 
committee said the reduction plan makes the arms control 
proposal that we have on the table much more relevant to the 
changing circumstances in europe and also much more in keeping with 
some of our fiscal pressures 
earlier in the day foley told reporters he would welcome a 
suggestion that we could make further troop cuts in europe 
i dont think the united states should totally withdraw from 
western europe but very substantial reductions are not only 
possible but i think inevitable he said 
bushs proposal is a response to the tumultuous changes in 
eastern europe where the push for democracy has led to the 
downfall of hardline communist regimes 
one longtime advocate of reduced us troops in europe rep 
patricia schroeder dcolo said she was delighted with the 
plan theres hope schroeder said 
just when you thought you had a cold war budget boom said 
schroeder a senior member of the house armed services committee 
aspin coupled his praise with a caution we should be careful 
in this whole process not to give the soviet union a reason to keep 
more troops in eastern europe than it would without an agreement 
for both sides it should be a ceiling not a floor 
rep pat williams dmont said bush is rushing to catch the 
reality of eastern europe 
sen william cohen rmaine said the united states was 
falling behind the curve of popular will on the issue of troop 
reductions 
rep dave mccurdy dokla a member of the house armed services 
committee and the democratic caucus pointman on defense 
questioned the absence of a military strategy from the 
administration 
it was unwise to build up on military strength in the 1980s 
without a national strategy but it is even more dangerous to build 
down without one mccurdy said 
dole defended the president as a middleoftheroad president 
ultra liberals and ultra conservatives may not like tonights 
speech which tells me george bush is right in step with the 
american people he said 
</TEXT>
