<TEXT>
a blizzard is blowing and dawn is an hour 
away but socialist candidate nobutaka tsutsui is shivering at a 
factory gate trying to entice votes away from the conservatives 
who have governed japan for 35 years 
wrapped in a wool coat and fortified by handwarmers in his 
pockets he zeroes in on the unpopular sales tax that the liberal 
democratic government introduced last year called a consumption 
tax in japan 
good morning my name is nobutaka tsutsui the smiling 
45yearold candidate for parliament tells workers as they arrive 
or leave during a shiftchange at an electronics factory 
lets join our forces to scrap the disgusting consumption tax 
and end the ldps tyranny 
no fancy speech about socialism and he gets encouraging 
responses even in this traditionally conservative ricegrowing 
constituency in northern japans snow country 
good luck says a young woman in a factory uniform i will 
vote for you to get rid of the consumption tax and so will many of 
my friends 
the socialists are counting on millions of likeminded people to 
knock the liberal democrats into the minority when ballots are 
counted from the feb 18 election which is expected to set the 
tone for japanese politics in the 1990s 
the conservative party appears to be facing the greatest threat 
ever to its dominance socialist candidates like tsutsui a 
populist lawyer who wears trendy clothes and moves around the 
snowbound district in a fourwheeldrive mitsubishi are expected 
to grab many normally conservative votes 
the liberal democratic party now holds 295 of the 512 seats in 
the lower house of parliament polls indicate it could lose its 
majority in the chamber which elects the prime minister 
the socialists are the largest opposition group and have a 
chance to increase their seats from 85 now to more than 140 under 
the leadership of popular chairwoman takako doi 
if that happens and the parties with their deep ideological 
divides try to form a coalition government japan could be headed 
for a period of political uncertainty 
tsutsui fell 7000 votes short of a seat in the last election in 
1986 but he is regarded as frontrunner among a halfdozen 
candidates vying for the two seats in the constituency 
i am aware i have some advantages this time he said as he 
plowed through the snow in a jeep but my weakness is that i 
still lack prominence compared with the liberal democrat 
incumbents 
if tsutsui wins one of the two liberal democrat incumbents will 
be out fourterm legislator katsuhiko shirakawa 44 is trying 
hard to win that other seat 
this is nothing but a fight for political survival for me 
shirakawa said as he was driven from one campaign stop to the next 
he told about 25 factory managers who gathered at a supporters 
house in rural takada i can protect the interests of people in 
the jyoetsu district and make the area thrive 
new train lines and new highways are going to be built in the 
next four to six years as a result of my efforts said shirakawa 
fixing his gaze on each person in the audience in turn we can 
expect a huge amount of public works followed by hundreds of 
thousands of tourists and new business opportunities 
pork barrel politics is the origin of much of the liberal 
democrats success over past decades as they spread public works 
around japan enabling them to campaign on a record of bringing 
local prosperity while building japan 
shirakawa is appealing to company executives smallbusiness 
owners and farmers trying to persuade them that he can help the 
local economy grow 
he says he has no way of stopping those who dislike the sales 
tax from voting socialist so he tries to strengthen my grip on 
the conservative votes and try not to let them go to the socialist 
or the other conservative party candidate 
the tax which imposes a 3 percent levy on all goods and 
services has become the focal point of the campaign polls 
indicate more than a third of voters pegged the tax as the no 1 
issue less than 10 percent thought the big issue was socialism vs 
conservatism the liberal democrats campaign theme 
hurt by sex and bribery scandals and the sales tax the liberal 
democrats lost their majority in the upper house in july elections 
and two prime ministers from the party had to resign last year in 
an extraordinary show of political disarray 
opposition parties are united in their calls to scrap the tax 
entirely the liberal democrats insist it is essential to support 
the budget in the 21st century though they promise to review and 
improve the tax 
i just hope that too many voters wont turn to the 
socialists only because of the tax issue disregarding other 
important national and international issues shirakawa told about 
50 female workers at a backers semiconductor factory who had 
gathered during a lunch break 
at about the same time tsutsui was kneeling on a reedmat floor 
with about 25 people in the home of a supporter telling them 
japan needs a new type of leadership that is fitting for a new 
era but the ldp is suffering from metal fatigue and it must be 
replaced 
and the very first thing we should do is to scrap the 
consumption tax which we all hate the tax has a symbolic 
significance of what a long oneparty dominance will cause 
</TEXT>
