<TEXT>
julia davis stuart a former president of 
the league of women voters of the united states has died at her 
home she was 79 
mrs stuart who died saturday was national president from 1964 
to 1968 she was the first westerner to hold that office 
during her tenure as national president mrs stuart was noted 
for extensive work in conservation of water resources 
in 1969 she was honored on the 50th anniversary of the league 
by president richard nixon at a white house ceremony mrs stuart 
also served on president lyndon johnsons 19member commission of 
law enforcement and administration of justice and on the national 
citizens commission on international cooperation 
mrs stuart was born in missouri and graduated from the 
university of missouri she and her husband robert j stuart came 
to bellingham from oklahoma in 1951 and moved to spokane five years 
later 
mrs stuart joined the league of women voters in spokane and was 
president of that chapter from 1951 to 1953 she later served four 
years as washington state president 
in 1960 she was elected to the national board and two years 
later became national second vice president she was twice elected 
president of the league of women voters of the united states 
she is survived by her husband robert j a son two daughters 
and three grandchildren 
</TEXT>
