<TEXT>
the most powerful nuclear research 
reactor of its kind has resumed limited operation at the oak ridge 
national laboratory after being shut down for more than three years 
by safety concerns 
the high flux isotope reactor was restarted monday department 
of energy spokesman steve wyatt said 
he said the reactor which has a maximum power of 85 megawatts 
will operate at no more than 11 megawatts for the next few weeks as 
part of a training and testing exercise for operators 
a schedule for resuming full power will depend on the outcome of 
the tests 
the reactor is used to produce and study heavy manmade 
elements it also supplies special isotopes for medical and 
industrial use and is used in irradiation testing for fusion and 
fission reactor development 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

