<TEXT>
prosecutors appear to be building a drug case 
against mayor marion barry by securing the cooperation of a man who 
law enforcement sources say accused the mayor of drug use 
james mcwilliams a district of columbia employee pleaded 
guilty to a misdemeanor drug charge tuesday and then immediately 
began testifying before a grand jury investigating barrys ties to 
convicted drug dealer charles lewis 
this is another significant step in this investigation us 
attorney jay b stephens said the mayors arrest was a 
significant step and this was a significant step too 
in another development a source familiar with the case said 
several members of the mayors city security detail are expected to 
testify before the grand jury in the near future 
the guards who are assigned to the mayor on a roundtheclock 
basis are expected to be asked whether they ever witnessed the 
mayor using drugs or helped get drugs for him said the source who 
spoke on condition of anonymity 
at a news conference stephens refused to say whether he intends 
for the bodyguards to testify before the panel but said 
prosecutors will want to cover any witness that might be able to 
provide information regarding this case 
barry who was arrested jan 18 on a misdemeanor cocaine 
possession charge has denied under oath using drugs with lewis at 
a downtown washington hotel more than a year earlier in december 
1988 
the charge against mcwilliams stemmed from allegations of visits 
to lewis hotel room some of which prosecutors say coincided with 
barrys visits 
meanwhile washingtons wrctv quoting unnamed sources said 
barry could be indicted within two weeks by the grand jury which 
has been looking into allegations of perjury and cocaine possession 
mcwilliams a city motor vehicles department employee and a 
longtime lewis associate declined to comment either before or 
after his grand jury testimony he pleaded guilty to a charge of 
aiding and abetting drug possession which carries a maximum 
penalty of one year in prison and a 100000 fine 
according to a source familiar with the case mcwilliams has 
told authorities he was present once when the mayor and lewis 
disappeared into the bathroom of the hotel room for a short time 
mcwilliams told prosecutors he smelled crack cocaine and then 
saw the mayor emerge from the bathroom under the influence of the 
drug the source said 
the washington post in todays editions quoted assistant us 
attorney richard w roberts as saying that during the hotel 
episode mcwilliams loaned money to lewis for lewis to purchase 
drugs and later lent his car to lewis so that lewis could go 
purchase additional drugs 
mcwilliams 57 was called before the grand jury investigating 
the case last january but refused to testify 
carole bland jackson a former business partner of the woman who 
was in a hotel room when barry was arrested this month in an fbi 
sting also said in weekend interviews that she was present when 
barry used cocaine at a 1986 party 
the mayor is in florida at a private facility being treated for 
what aides say is primarily an alcohol abuse problem 
lewis pleaded guilty to cocaine conspiracy charges last november 
in washington and was convicted on cocaine distribution charges in 
the virgin islands last spring 
lewis who is cooperating with prosecutors testified under oath 
during his plea bargaining session in november that he supplied 
barry with crack cocaine 
in meetings with prosecutors in the past week mcwilliams also 
said the mayor called him after barrys ties to lewis became public 
and told him he trusted him to keep quiet about what he had seen in 
the hotel room two law enforcement sources said 
barry has said he only called mcwilliams to urge him to 
cooperate with authorities investigating the case 
