<TEXT>
thousands of starving people are being 
held captive in the besieged southern capital of juba where rebels 
and army forces are at a standoff in some of the civil wars 
fiercest fighting relief workers say 
the relief workers who were evacuated from the city this week 
said tuesday that government soldiers have prevented residents from 
leaving so many people are digging trenches to shelter themselves 
from rocket attacks by rebels ringing the city 
juba has become a death trap said irishman daniel eiffe 
people live in terror from the shelling this is a whole new 
dimension 
eiffe of the agency for cooperation and research in 
development a londonbased relief group flew to khartoum on 
monday with three other westerners as part of a un airlift 
fourteen other westerners flew to nairobi kenya and they too 
spoke of terror and starvation an italian doctor said he saw 
security forces beat back two groups of people attempting to leave 
mainly women and children 
civilians fleeing the fighting in the countryside have swollen 
jubas population to nearly 300000 and food is running out 
another doctor who fled to nairobi said people fear riots over the 
meager stocks that remain 
the angst is exacerbated by the uncertainty of what will come if 
rebels of the sudan peoples liberation army end their long siege 
of the city with a military advance 
the rebels end broadcasts on their clandestine radio station 
with the ominous signoff black people be ready 
john garang a renegade army colonel began the bush insurgency 
in africas largest country in 1983 the rebels are fighting the 
moslemdominated government in khartoum for increased economic and 
political autonomy for the predominantly christian and animist 
southern half of sudan 
hundreds of thousands have died in the civil war most of them 
victims of a famine caused by farmers being driven from their 
fields to seek refuge in governmentcontrolled places like juba 
750 miles south of the capital 
the rebel push around juba is their fiercest offensive in nearly 
seven years they have captured 11 communities south and west of 
the city virtually ending access to it by road 
the army has 9000 to 10000 troops and several thousand armed 
civilians and militia in juba which sits on the west bank of the 
white nile and is the largest town in southern sudan 
about 5000 rebels are thought to surround the city and 
military sources in khartoum said the insurgents lack the firepower 
or manpower to take juba 
the rebels have shelled the city twice on jan 21 and last 
friday eiffe said at least 23 civilians were killed in the 
attacks on monday rebel radio said the shelling would resume and 
advised residents to leave 
eiffe said the city was paralyzed he said businesses and 
schools were closed and food distribution so limited that rations 
were half of what is considered minimal daily fare under 
international standards more than half of jubas residents are 
displaced people who live in crude camps 
the government banned relief flights to the south on nov 3 
because of intensified fighting and jubas only source of food has 
been daily sudan airways flights chartered by the lutheran world 
federation in nairobi 
the flights bring in 50 to 60 tons of food a day but the city 
needs 150 tons a day to adequately feed people relief workers say 
the sudan airways pilots are very brave eiffe said they 
fly in despite attacks on them 
thousands of people gather around the sudan airways office in 
juba trying to get tickets out he said they fly out around 80 
to 100 sudanese daily 
eiffe said juba residents fearing new shelling had been crowding 
into his office begging for shovels and picks to dig bunkers in 
which to hide others fled to the deep banks of the nile for 
protection 
some of the western evacuees blamed both the army and the rebels 
for jubas desperation all spoke on condition they not be 
identified by name or organization 
they said the rebels shelled juba indiscriminately with rockets 
that make terrifying noises when they explode and burst into 
hundreds of pieces of maiming shrapnel 
the army in turn has planted land mines as part of a security 
cordon around the city the evacuees said the troops also refuse to 
let residents leave apparently hoping their presence will keep the 
rebels from trying to invade 
one evacuee said many juba residents sympathize with the rebel 
cause but nobody can understand their purpose in shelling the city 
he said residents listen to government and rebel propaganda and 
feel trapped in the middle 
a few weeks ago food was the major concern eiffe said 
now thats changed and its terror from shelling 
</TEXT>
