<TEXT>
scientists say they are 
delighted with the condition of a rescued science satellite 
because the wear and tear it received during six years in space was 
just what they wanted 
thats why we sent it up there to find out what happens to 
materials after a long time in the space environment william h 
kinard project chief said tuesday after getting his first look at 
the satellite since its return 
wearing contaminationproof clothing and standing on an 
observation platform several feet away kinard and other scientists 
watched as the shuttle columbias 60footlong cargo bay doors 
swung open to reveal the 11ton satellite known as the long 
duration exposure facility 
columbias astronauts retrieved the laboratory 200 miles in 
space on jan 12 snaring it just weeks before it probably would 
have been dragged by gravity to a fiery death in the atmosphere 
the satellite eventually will be moved to a nearby sterilized 
building for close examination 
at the johnson space center in houston the commander of the 
shuttle mission said the damage to the experiments aboard the 
laboratory will provide clues to what materials best withstand the 
harsh environment of space 
i think it does certainly bring home the point that we have to 
take a good look at anything we do over a long duration in space 
commander dan brandenstein told reporters tuesday 
kinard said the laboratory appeared to have suffered a little 
more wear and tear than the pictures taken by the astronauts in 
space indicated 
it looked a little more weathered than we concluded earlier 
he said there are lots of small micrometeoroid craters and there 
are some other places where there are reactions that may have been 
started my micrometeoroids 
he said there was some discoloration and that foil covering some 
experiments had been torn 
were delighted with the condition kinard said 
there are 57 experiments attached to the satellites exterior 
and scientists and engineers are eager to see how the various 
materials in them fared during their long exposure to atomic 
oxygen radiation micrometeoroids and other phenomena in space 
the results will help in designing future longduration 
spacecraft including the freedom manned space station to be 
assembled in orbit starting in 1995 
four teams will study the recovered laboratory here for about 
three weeks photographing it and jotting down their observations 
the teams are composed of specialists in space debris materials 
spacecraft systems and radiation 
starting in midfebruary the experiments will be covered with 
protective aluminum and removed onebyone from the satellites 
racks they then will be delivered to scientists throughout the 
nation and western europe for detailed study 
the satellite carries 21 materials coating and thermal systems 
experiments five power and propulsion experiments 17 science 
experiments and 14 optics and electronic experiments they 
represent more than 200 investigators 33 private companies 21 
universities seven national aeronautics and space administration 
centers and eight foreign countries 
also aboard are 125 million tomato seeds a few will be planted 
in research labs but most will be sent to schools where students 
from fifth grade through university level will plant water and 
nurture the seeds for research into such things as germination 
rates chromosome and genetics studies and full tomato growth 
kinard said the seeds will be among the first experiments 
removed so that the students have time to work with them before 
the school year ends 
