<TEXT>
as the africanized killer bees 
swarm ever closer to their longawaited us border crossing 
scientists are meeting to develop a strategy for battling the 
invasion which may occur by the spring 
the bees were sighted recently at soto la marina mexico about 
150 miles south of the border city of brownsville said anita 
collins bee reseach leader for the local agricultural research 
service station 
scientists from the research service the department of 
agricultures animal and plant health inspection service and the 
texas aampm agricultural experiment station attended a bee strategy 
meeting tuesday 
we are trying to draft specific plans for who is going to do 
what and when and how when we start seeing bees coming across the 
border collins said and the idea is to protect the public and 
the bee industry in texas 
there is no reason to panic collins said 
it is not a black cloud about to descend on south texas she 
said this is the natural spread of a population in small groups 
of bees called swarms 
the killer bees buzz off when sprayed with insect repellent 
and if no repellent is available the best advice is to run 
because you can outrun a bee collins said 
the bees a hybrid of the european honeybee and the pure african 
queen bee gained the killer label not because their sting is 
more poisonous than the european bees but because of their 
defensive behavior in which hundreds or thousands of the bees 
attack intruders 
twentysix africanized queen bees that escaped a research center 
in brazil in 1957 are to blame for the swarms that have crept 
steadily northward through central american and mexico 
the bees spread at the rate of 200300 miles annually according 
to research by john thomas a texas aampm extension entomologist 
texas aampm sought 690000 for a control program to slow the bee 
spread but the state legislature turned down the request last year 
said fred meyer of the us agriculture department 
once the bees arrive meyer said funds should be available to 
eradicate the hives of the africanized bees survey the areas where 
they are found and quarantine bees in affected areas 
several swarms of africanized bees that arrived on ships from 
latin america already have been found at seaports in the united 
states 
