<TEXT>
thousands of people live in fear and have a right 
to know if rocky flats has adversely effected their health says 
the attorney who filed two classaction lawsuits against the 
nuclear weapons plants former operators 
also tuesday a 2 billion lawsuit was filed in ohio against a 
former operator of another federally owned nuclear factory the 
fernald uranium processing plant nlo inc and its parent company 
were accused of subjecting employees to a hazardous radioactive 
workplace 
the denver lawsuits allege that rockwell international corp and 
its predecessor dow chemical co were careless and negligent in 
the treatment of hazardous wastes at rocky flats the plant 16 
miles northwest of denver has manufactured plutonium triggers for 
nuclear weapons since 1953 
energy secretary james watkins suspended plutonium processing 
operations at rocky flats in november he said the shutdown would 
remain in effect until doe is convinced safety and health standards 
are being met 
the lawsuits filed in us district court seek independent study 
of health risks posed by the nuclear weapons plant 250 million in 
economic damages for devaluation of property and 300 million in 
other damages former workers also want an unspecified amount of 
money because the stigma of their past employment prevents them 
from finding new jobs or health insurance 
they the plaintiffs want to be told the truth by someone who 
is independent and not controlled by the government or the 
operators of rocky flats said attorney bruce deboskey 
this is not a lawsuit to close rocky flats but to have it run 
properly he said 
the lawsuits said that actions by dow and rockwell led to 
repeated releases of both radioactive and nonradioactive hazardous 
substances into the atmosphere and violations of state and federal 
environmental health and safety laws 
five neighbors of the plant filed one of the lawsuits on behalf 
of about 10000 property owners and up to 50000 people who live 
near the plant they asked the court to halt the further releases 
of hazardous substances 
dow chemical operated the plant from 1953 until 1975 when 
rockwell took over last year the department of energy replaced 
rockwell with egampg inc after the fbi and the environmental 
protection agency raided rocky flats looking for evidence of 
illegal disposal of hazardous wastes 
the other lawsuit was filed by the building and construction 
trades department aflcio and the construction trades council on 
behalf of more than 10000 current and former plant workers 
that suit asks the court to order the defendants to create a 
fund to finance reasonable medical monitoring and surveillance 
including independent scientific studies of adverse health effects 
rockwell officials in el segundo calif declined to comment 
saying they had not seen the court documents dow chemical 
officials at company headquarters in midland mich did not reply 
to calls seeking comment 
deboskey said the lawsuits stem from peoples concern and 
their fear over whether or not they have lost money and whether or 
not their health has been affected by the operations at the plant 
that fear was heightened by the fbi raid last summer 
deboskey said in a telephone interview people are afraid 
theyre afraid and they want to know the truth from people other 
than the ones who have caused the pollution 
doe last year identified rocky flats as the most hazardous site 
in the nations nuclear weapons complex saying toxic chemicals 
contaminated an underground reservoir and threatened nearby city 
water supplies 
the ohio lawsuit filed in us district court in cincinnati 
accused nlo and parent nl industries inc of failing to properly 
store or contain highly radioactive substances at the feed 
materials production center in fernald 
the plant 18 miles northwest of cincinnati processes uranium 
for the energy departments production of nuclear weapons 
the lawsuit says the employees suffered loss of income 
emotional distress including increased fear of cancer and 
diminished ability to obtain other jobs or insurance 
it seeks 2 billion in damages plus unspecified punitive damages 
and payment for extended medical monitoring of the employees 
</TEXT>
