<TEXT>
a princeton university graduate has asked 
the state supreme court to require two campus eating clubs to admit 
women 
sally frank now an instructor on discrimination cases at new 
york law school on tuesday urged the high court to end what she 
called 21 years of discrimination at the ivy club and the tiger 
inn which do not admit women 
ms frank said the clubs and princeton university have a 
symbiotic relationship that removes them from protection under 
laws governing private organizations 
but attorneys for the clubs compared the groups to fraternities 
and sororities and said they have the right to choose their own 
members 
we have to make the distinction between civil rights and 
social relationships said barbara strapp nelson who represented 
the ivy club whether one should maintain a social relationship 
with another is not regulated by the state 
the clubs are among 13 private eating clubs at princeton most 
of the juniors and seniors at princeton eat at these clubs which 
are in privatelyowned houses near the campus 
since princeton began admitting women in 1969 only the ivy club 
and the tiger inn have refused to change their rules and admit 
females 
the high court heard the case after a three judge panel of the 
appellate division of superior court last year reversed a 1987 
decision by the state division on civil rights the civil rights 
agency had ordered the clubs to admit women 
ms frank who began her protest as a junior at princeton in 
1979 said the university has billed the eating club in its 
publications as part of the princeton experience 
deputy attorney general susan reisner one of several attorneys 
who represented ms franks case said the clubs had such a close 
connection to princeton they could not claim exemption to 
antidiscrimination laws as a strictly private club 
attorneys for the clubs countered that the clubs are not part of 
the university 
russell beatie jr representing the tiger inn said the case 
pits discrimination laws and privacy laws 
he accused ms frank of seeking admission for purposes other 
than a true desire to be a member of the tiger inn calling her 
energy looking for a cause 
attorneys for the clubs asked the court to give them another 
hearing to dispute facts presented by ms franks attorneys 
ms frank estimated after the hearing that if the court returns 
the matter to a lower level it could take six more years to 
settle however she vowed to continue her fight 
there is a continuing and ongoing interest by female 
students to join these clubs ms frank said 
</TEXT>
