<TEXT>
frederick w winterbotham who played a key role 
in exploiting broken german codes in world war ii and wrote the 
bestselling memoir the ultra secret died sunday of natural 
causes at age 92 
winterbotham was a pilot in world war i and in 1929 was made 
head of aerial intelligence in mi6 the british intelligence agency 
in the 1930s he befriended senior nazi figures in germany and 
gleaned information about the luftwaffe in 1939 he helped devise a 
vital new method of aerial reconnaissance photography 
his most important work was with enigma the topsecret 
german code system that the british had managed to penetrate 
his work made him a confidant of wartime prime minister winston 
churchill but he remained an unsung war hero because the cracking 
of enigma was considered so secret it was not revealed until 30 
years after the war when he published the ultra secret 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
chesley peterson a highly decorated flying 
ace and the us air forces youngest colonel died sunday in 
riverside calif he was 69 
the retired air force major general had suffered from heart and 
lung disease 
in 1940 peterson went to england to join the royal air forces 
eagle squadron a group of foreign volunteers flying hawker 
hurricanes and supermarine spitfires in battles with the german 
luftwaffe peterson advanced to squadron commander at age 21 and 
colonel at 23 
he kept the rank when he moved to the us army air corps to fly 
p47 thunderbolts in 1943 he remains the air forces youngestever 
colonel 
in more than 200 combat missions peterson claimed nine kills 
and nine more probable kills twice parachuting from damaged 
spitfires 
he is the only american fighter pilot to win the us 
distinguished service cross and britains distinguished service 
order according to airman magazine 
</TEXT>
