<TEXT>
a political reform initiative that won 
voter approval 19 months ago has wound up like many so many other 
california ballot measures in recent years in court 
testimony began tuesday in the federal court trial of 
proposition 73 the omnibus campaign cleanup measure that outlawed 
public financing of political races limited contributions and 
banned transfers of donations between candidates committees 
the proposition is the latest in a series of voterapproved 
ballot questions including measures dealing with insurance rate 
reform and toxics cleanup that have become ensnared in legal 
tangles 
opponents of proposition 73 led by assembly speaker willie 
brown the democratic party and several unions want us district 
judge lawrence karlton to throw out the initiative they contend it 
is unconstitutional and denies women minorities and grassroots 
groups their rights by unfairly limiting the amount of money they 
can raise to run against wealthy incumbents 
in addition an advocate for one of the states most powerful 
and wellheeled lobbies the 240000member california teachers 
association testified that proposition 73 has put a crimp in the 
teachers political activities 
alice huffman who heads the associations political action 
committee that distributes hundred of thousands of dollars annually 
to legislative candidates said the measures contribution 
restraints restrict the groups contacts with its members by 
limiting the number of campaign endorsement letters it can send 
the authors of proposition 73 said their initiative is supported 
by the public and opposed only by democratic politicians seeking to 
bolster their power 
opposition is coming from some of the most powerful 
politicians and special interests in california said initiative 
coauthor ross johnson of fullerton the republican leader of the 
state assembly those groups dislike provisions that apply the same 
limits to all candidates he said 
johnson said the initiative has hamstrung runaway campaign 
donations but critics including the political watchdog group 
common cause contend the measure has had an uncertain impact on 
californias highstakes political campaigns 
joseph garcia an attorney for the state fair political 
practices commission said the lawsuit was politically motivated 
and not based on merit 
in this case these facts are about politics and these 
plaintiffs are politicians garcia said not here before the 
court today are the three million voters who overwhelmingly 
approved proposition 73 in 1988 by 58 percent of the vote 
the measure was approved 314 million to 223 million votes 
the initiative puts a 1000 ceiling on individual contributions 
to a state or local candidate in a single fiscal year 2500 from 
a political committee and 5000 from a socalled broadbased 
political action committee or political party the measure put no 
restrictions on spending 
on may 19 karlton ruled in favor of the plaintiffs issuing a 
temporary order that overturned some provisions the judge lifted 
the ban on transfers between one candidates committees removed 
the limit on labor union contributions for endorsement mailings 
and said candidates could use funds raised before jan 1 1989 
when most of the provisions took effect to back or oppose other 
candidates 
his order remains in effect pending the outcome of the trial 
karlton is hearing the case without a jury and he said the 
trial will probably be completed by early next week 
other initiatives that have resulted in court fights include 
proposition 103 the insurance reform measure backed by consumer 
advocate ralph nader and proposition 65 the antitoxics 
cleanwater initiative that was supported by environmentalists but 
opposed by farmers and manufacturers 
