<TEXT>
arnaud dusseau a broadway playwright and 
hollywood screenwriter who was blacklisted after a heated 
confrontation with sen joseph mccarthy has died at 73 
dusseau died monday of complications of surgery for stomach 
cancer in new york city the los angeles times reported today 
the author of such acclaimed plays as tomorrow the world and 
deep are the roots was brought before mccarthy in 1953 as the 
senator investigated alleged communist influence in the film 
industry 
dusseau refused to answer mccarthys questions saying he would 
be happy to debate the merits of communism and capitalism in 
another setting but not where you have everything stacked 
at one point the republican senator from wisconsin threatened 
to remove dusseau from the hearing room 
after his blacklisting dusseau wrote for films under 
pseudonyms his last play bledsoe is being readied for a 
broadway opening 
a native of los angeles dusseau began writing professionally 
in the 1930s his films included one crowded night lady 
scarface repent at leisure just off broadway the man 
who wouldnt die and who is hope schuyler 
in 1944 ring lardner jr who became one of the socalled 
hollywood 10 group of writers and directors who went to prison for 
their defiance of the congressional investigations of alleged 
communist influence adapted dusseaus tomorrow the world for 
the screen 
considered among the most literate of the wartime propaganda 
works tomorrow the world was about a german boy adopted by an 
american couple 
in 1945 dusseau and his writing partner james gow created 
deep are the roots which explored the thencontroversial theme 
of miscegenation as it pleaded for racial tolerance 
dusseaus other broadway plays included ladies of the 
corridor written with dorothy parker and the legend of 
sarah with gow in 1950 
dusseau lived in new york and taught writing at new york 
university and the school of visual arts 
survivors include his wife marie a son a daughter and three 
brothers 
funeral arrangements were not immediately known 
