<TEXT>
defense minister yitzhak rabin today ordered a 
temporary halt to the expulsion of palestinians living in the 
occupied territories without residency permits a practice that has 
torn apart hundreds of families 
the announcement which cited humanitarian reasons came a day 
after the us state department expressed concern over the 
expulsions 
palestinian activists claim the expulsions have been stepped up 
and are part of a longterm strategy to force palestinians out of 
the occupied west bank and gaza strip where the palestinian 
uprising against israeli authority has claimed hundreds of lives 
over the last 26 months 
israeli officials deny the claim 
according to an army official 251 palestinians including 88 
women and 78 children were expelled from the occupied lands in the 
past year because they did not have residency permits 
the official did not have figures for preceding years 
rabin told reporters today he decided to stop expulsions and 
review the policy to prevent a case in which half a family will 
be forced out while another part will be allowed to stay 
he indicated however that expulsions would resume we cannot 
afford in principle that a person who comes as a tourist or as a 
visitor takes the liberty to stay forever he said 
the armyrun government in the occupied lands has adopted 
stringent residency regulations under which only palestinians who 
lived in the occupied lands during a september 1967 census are 
automatically eligible for permits 
others must apply for permits and the vast majority of 
applications are turned down 
rabin told parliament tuesday that since 1967 military 
officials have received 88429 requests for family 
reunification and that 13509 of those were granted 
the group most affected is palestinian women whose families fled 
to jordan when israel seized the west bank and gaza in the 1967 
middle east war and who later married men from the occupied lands 
inevitably these women and their children become part of the 
demographic war between israel and the palestinians 
some palestinians see increasing their numbers as a way to give 
weight to their argument for statehood at the same time israel 
wants to limit the number of arabs under its control 
wives denied residency permits usually enter the occupied lands 
on threemonth visitor visas and then face the choice of leaving 
their families and returning to jordan or staying illegally 
palestinian human rights groups have said that in the past few 
months soldiers have raided several remote west bank villages to 
round up illegal residents placed them in taxis and escorted them 
to the allenby bridge which links jordan and the west bank 
the expulsions universally take place in the middle of the 
night with no immediate warning wrote the palestinian news 
service sanabel which published details of several cases 
rabins announcement of freezing the expulsions came after 
statement department spokeswoman margaret tutwiler said tuesday 
that israeli officials are well aware of our concern 
particularly with regard to divided families 
the swift israeli response came at a time when usisraeli 
relations are strained over differences on how to make peace with 
palestinians and when some american politicians are urging cuts in 
aid to the jewish state 
also today arab activists stabbed to death a palestinian 
suspect of collaborating with israel and israeli soldiers shot and 
wounded three palestinians in the occupied territories arab 
reports said 
a strike ordered by the plolinked underground leadership of the 
uprising brought transportation to a halt and kept students out of 
school 
the death of 35yearold adwa aziz el masri a taxi driver 
brought to 175 the number of palestinians killed after being 
accused of collaborating with israel at least 651 palestinians 
have died of israeli gunfire during the rebellion and 43 israelis 
have been slain 
</TEXT>
