more than 100000 slavs some firing 
guns in the air demonstrated in at least three yugoslav cities 
today to demand a halt to protests by ethnic albanians in the 
ethnically troubled province of kosovo 
new protests by albanians were reported today in at least five 
kosovo cities a day after unrest claimed five lives 
a speaker at the biggest antialbanian rally in the capital of 
the montenegrin republic said volunteers were signing up to fight 
ethnic albanians themselves unless authorities use all available 
methods including repression to end the albanian uprising 
belgrade television showed footage of the huge rally in 
titograd the commentator estimated the crowd at 100000 
in the montenegrin town of ivangrad 10000 people demonstrated 
against albanian separatists and slovenian and croatian leaders 
supporting them the official tanjug news agency reported 
the reformist leaders of the republics of slovenia and croatia 
have supported the ethnic albanians demands for more autonomy in 
kosovo 
in belgrade the federal capital tens of thousands of people 
rallied in what also was billed as a demonstration against the 
ethnic albanians but shouts of down with communism also were 
heard 
earlier 5000 students gathered outside parliament in belgrade 
demanding weapons to defend slavs in kosovo where five people were 
reported killed in clashes tuesday between the ethnic albanian 
majority and police 
official media said the situation in kosovo was approaching 
civil war since the latest clashes broke out jan 24 official 
media have reported 13 deaths 
the albanians want to regain the autonomy lost when the serbian 
republic took control of kosovos police judiciary and education 
last year kosovo is a province within serbia and borders albania 
the slav minority which includes serbs and montenegrins 
contends the albanians were trying to force them from their 
homeland and that increased control over the region was necessary 
belgrade radio said today that at vucitrn 20 miles northwest of 
the kosovo capital of pristina five demonstrators sustained 
unspecified injuries apparently in clashes with police 
about 3000 demonstrators assembled in podujevo the scene of a 
major clash tuesday and approximately 1000 others rallied at 
streoci 
police used tear gas to prevent 200 demonstrators from joining 
another crowd of protesters on the streets of titova mitrovica and 
an unspecified number of protesters rallied in ada 
at malisevo where two deaths were reported tuesday thousands 
of ethnic albanians turned out for the funerals of three of their 
brethren killed in the unrest 
the students in belgrade proclaimed a general strike and 
demanded the resignation of the highest organs of the 
federation unless what they termed nationalist and vandalist 
rioting of ethnic albanian terrorists in kosovo is not halted 
within 48 hours 
we shall give our lives but not kosovo they chanted 
they also chanted hang azem vlasi referring to the former 
communist leader of kosovo who is on trial for allegedly inciting 
ethnic albanians to riot nearly a year ago 
kosovo is closer to civil war that it was ever before said 
the oslobodjenje daily in the city of sarajevo whether kosovo 
will become even bloodier is a question which no one can answer 
the situation is dramatic and uncertain and it is hard to predict 
what will take place within an hour or two not to mention 
tomorrow 
the proserb communist leadership of the kosovo town of titova 
mitrovica said unless steps are taken for suppression and 
protection from terrorist actions of albanian nationalists and 
separatists the situation threatens to grow into civil war 
serbs and ethnic albanians were reported confronting each other 
in the town of kosovska vitina on tuesday the first time this has 
happened 
a number of serbian villages have organized vigilante patrols 
armed with shotguns and pistols 
