<TEXT>
the national the nations only allsports 
daily hit the newsstands today tempting sportshungry americans 
with a 48page menu that included everthing from statistics to 
gossip jock stocks and a weather map 
the 50cent tabloid was distributed to vendors in new york los 
angeles and chicago plans are to expand to other big cities such 
as detroit dallas philadelphia boston and san francisco with a 
target of 15 cities by the end of 1990 
publisher peter o price and editor frank deford said at a news 
conference that the first issue got out with few glitches price 
said about 250000 copies were distributed and that he had been 
told many new york newsstands sold out fairly quickly 
price conceded that there was a novelty effect to the 
firstday sales but said he was convinced there was immense 
demand for the paper anyway deford said he expects the paper to 
be so successful that someone may try to imitate it 
the national is owned by national american sports communications 
lp a partnership that includes price and mexican media baron 
emilio azcarraga deford a former sports illustrated writer heads 
the 125person editorial staff 
while initial sales plans are limited to singlecopy sales at 
newstands and in vending boxes deford said the paper hopes to 
offer maildelivery subscriptions later this year so more people 
can get it 
with a startup cost of 25 million the partnership has 
acknowledged that it may take several years before the newspaper 
turns a profit price said azcarraga was prepared to spend 100 
million to put it in the black 
todays edition contained 36 pages of editorial material and 12 
of advertisements many of them color among the advertisers were 
cbs sports mci communications toyota the trump shuttle and nike 
whose centerfold ad read halftime 
inside were a variety of stories analysis color photos and 
slickly presented statistics 
the weather map detailed conditions in cities where games and 
other sporting events are being held a playground section 
featured a crossword puzzle and comics the paper also included a 
gossip column and even a brief listing of stocks of sportsoriented 
companies labeled jock stocks 
the newspaper claimed two exclusives one dealing with 
rightfielder darryl strawberry threatening to leave the mets and 
the other reporting florida running back emmitt smiths decision to 
turn pro 
news outside the sporting arena was not totally ignored the 
first issue devoted a half page to the real world led by a 
brief story on the rumor that mikhail gorbachev plans to resign his 
post as leader of the soviet communist party the real news 
also featured briefs on zsa zsa gabor and bob dylan 
the paper is being published sunday through friday 
