here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers 
throughout the country 
jan 30 
the clarionledger jackson miss on bushs budget 
president bushs budget is sure to get reworked by congress and 
one area that can be targeted is reducing the nations military 
expenditures overseas 
for example cia director william webster has told congress the 
intelligence agency concludes that the soviet threat to the united 
states and its nato allies has diminished due to the democratizing 
changes in eastern europe 
that echoed remarks by gen colin powell chairman of the us 
joint chiefs of staff after an unprecedented meeting in vienna of 
western and warsaw pact top military brass he said there is 
nothing sacrosanct about the number of american troops stationed in 
europe 
czechoslovakia and hungary already have said they want soviet 
troops off their soil this year east germany has proposed that all 
foreign troops leave both germanys by 1999 and soviet leader 
mikhail gorbachev has already said it is his goal to pull all 
soviet troops off foreign soil 
savings from further trimming the overseas military budget could 
be used in reducing the federal deficit we now have a chance to 
start turning some spears into plowshares to make america even 
stronger 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jan 30 
los angeles times on bushs budget 
if nothing else president bushs budget should stifle the 
notion that talk is cheap it mentions by name one serious problem 
after another yet makes clear that most of them will be around 
long after washington spends the allotted 123 trillion 
the white house has doctored forecasts of economic growth and 
interest rates to make it seem as if the deficit will shrink from 
100 billion to a mere 64 billion economists generally think that 
the national debt could well grow by as much as bush promises it 
will shrink leaving the worlds most prosperous nation still 
living way beyond its means 
the president again puts politics and a campaign promise ahead 
of smart policy and rules out even minimal increases in taxes that 
could get government out of the red congress may fuss at bush for 
capricious bookkeeping but it knows as well as he that voters are 
less likely to punish politicians for higher deficits than for 
higher taxes 
even in the absence of new taxes congress and the white house 
will find ways to keep busy bushs proposal to shut down 35 
military bases each of them in the home district of some member of 
congress is bound to provide weeks or even months of argument over 
whether closing some other base would yield greater savings 
congress probably will cut the 45 billion the white house wants 
for star wars research fight to spare domestic programs bush 
would fold and quarrel over the proper level of environmental 
protection 
but these are the ragged edges of governments obligations 
compared with the challenges of the national debt the future of 
social security rising healthcare costs education cleaning up 
nuclear waste and other gathering storms 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jan 26 
the pioneer bemidji minn on social security 
the debate over the use of excess social security funds is an 
interesting dilemma for policy makers and one that the bush 
administration is going to lose in the national public opinion 
polls 
most people werent aware until recently that the social 
security account has been showing a positive balance ever since the 
program was reengineered by congress 
the fund balance has been invested in us treasury notes 
savings bonds and other types of government investment programs 
and as a result the federal deficit has been reduced by almost 1 
billion a week over the past year thats a 50 billion reduction 
in the trade deficit 
opponents are saying that the funds should stay in the social 
security trust fund what these individuals fail to understand is 
that these funds are ultimately better being invested rather than 
laying dormant 
however we also feel that if investments are to be made there 
are far better choices than government securities private programs 
are administered for much higher returns 
</TEXT>
