<TEXT>
a coalition of church labor and policy groups 
launched a nationwide education effort wednesday to ensure that 
more than 11 million lowincome families receive a tax rebate for 
which they are eligible 
its a crime to think that this money is available and so many 
people are not taking advantage of it and they have earned it 
said james moran mayor of alexandria va 
most lowincome people know about medicaid public assistance 
food stamps school lunch and other government programs for the 
poor but significantly fewer have heard of the earned income 
credit said robert greenstein director of the center on budget 
and policy priorities an independent research group 
this is not a public assistance program its not a welfare 
program greenstein said it is an earned benefit that only 
families which work are eligible for and only families who live 
with and care for their children may receive 
the earned income tax credit was created by congress in 1974 to 
offset the impact of social security payroll taxes on the working 
poor families with at least one child living at home for half the 
year and earned or adjusted gross income of less than 19340 in 
1989 are eligible 
organizers didnt estimate how many families are eligible for 
the credit but said 11 million taxpayers received 6 billion in 
credits last year 
the groups planned to distribute 11000 information packets 
through churches civic groups and state and local government 
offices the aflcio also has produced a public service 
announcement in spanish 
the credit varies with individual households with annual income 
of between 6500 and 10240 a parent taxpayer is eligible for a 
910 credit families with income less than 6500 are eligible for 
a credit equal to 14 percent of that incoe 
the credit decreases once income exceeds 10240 and phases out 
at 19340 earned or adjusted gross income 
rural and hispanic families who make up a disproportionate 
number of lowincome wage earners and dont owe income tax will be 
a special target for the campaign 
the concern is that these families owing no federal income 
tax may believe that theres no need to file an income tax 
return greenstein said 
they may think that if they dont owe any income tax they 
cant get credit but the irs will mail them a check for the full 
amount of the credit for which they are eligible 
if they dont file the return they lose the credit greenstein 
said 
eligible workers can receive the credit in their regular 
paychecks throughout the year by filing a w5 form with their 
employers 
other groups in the coalition include the national council of la 
raza us catholic conference the national governors 
association the united way and the national restaurant association 
coalition members said they chose wednesday to begin their 
campaign because it marked the unofficial start of the 1989 income 
tax season and the last day for employers to mail w2 income 
withholding statements to workers 
