<TEXT>
the house interior committee voted wednesday 
to settle a 14yearold dispute among the seminole indians by 
giving 73 percent of about 50 million in federal damages to the 
oklahoma tribe and 27 percent to seminoles in florida 
the distribution differs from legislation passed in november by 
the senate that calls for an approximately 7525 split but it 
represents a compromise in the house where the florida delegation 
was seeking 30 percent of the money for its branch of the tribe 
the bill now goes to the full house for a vote and if approved 
in the form passed by the committee will go to a conference 
committee to work out differences with the senate version 
originally the florida seminoles pushed for a 5050 
distribution leading to a disagreement that the indians could not 
settle among themselves 
the dispute began in 1976 when the seminoles were awarded 16 
million for florida lands taken during the 1823 relocation of most 
of the tribe to oklahoma 
the money which has been held by the treasury department 
because of the disagreement over its distribution grew to 50 
million through years of accumulated interest 
in the absence of agreement among the seminoles the government 
worked out the 7525 split based on population figures that counted 
2146 seminoles in oklahoma and 700 in florida 
the government also found the oklahoma tribe to be poorer with 
only about 380 acres of tribally owned land while the florida 
branch which includes the miccosukee tribe of florida and the 
unaffiliated seminole indians of florida has about 80000 acres 
</TEXT>
