<TEXT>
attorney general dick thornburgh said 
wednesday there is a crisis over delays in carrying out the death 
penalty and he urged streamlining appeals procedures for death row 
inmates 
delay in the review and execution of capital sentences in this 
country has reached crisis proportions he told a committee 
studying federal court reform the average delay from time of 
conviction and sentence to time of execution of sentence in 1988 
was six years and eight months 
thornburgh endorsed proposals of a committee headed by retired 
supreme court justice lewis f powell calling for curtailing 
appeals in capital cases the powell committee also would give 
death row inmates a broader right to be represented by a lawyer at 
taxpayer expense 
the powell committee rcommended that states enact laws to limit 
death row inmates to two rounds of appeals in state and federal 
courts one round would challenge a verdict directly the second 
round would be based on alleged violations of the condemned 
individuals rights 
the current systems permits indefinite appeals in federal courts 
the attorney general said it is urgent to address the 
particularly acute problems of dilatory defense tactics and 
repetitive litigation in capital cases 
thornburgh also said he opposes plans to limit the power of 
federal courts to deal with drug law violations and shift 
enforcement to state courts 
it is becoming increasingly clear that many local drug 
networks have national sometimes international roots that demand 
a coordinated federal response he said 
thornburgh testified before the federal courts study committee 
created by congress to come up with plans by april for dealing with 
a host of problems and recommending changes 
the committee consisting of 15 members appointed by chief 
justice william h rehnquist heard testimony in a supreme court 
conference room from numerous judges public officials and lawyers 
the panel called for comment on a 140page draft report it 
released in december it hopes to have a final report in april to 
be submitted to congress president bush and rehnquist 
wednesdays session focused in part on the committees criticism 
of new sentencing guidelines in federal criminal cases 
thornburgh among others supported the guidelines and urged the 
committee to abandon its call for giving judges more freedom to 
depart from the guidelines 
while the guidelines do restrict the range of appropriate 
sentencing more than some judges might prefer that is the whole 
purpose of having them he said 
william w wilkins jr a federal appeals court judge who headed 
the commission that devised the guidelines said the federal courts 
study committee is proposing to abandon the guidelines based on 
flimsy evidence 
congress may have underestimated the need for more resources 
to implement guidelines sentencing wilkins said the answer to 
that problem would appear to be for this committee to recommend 
more judicial resources not to call for virtual repeal of the 
law that authorized the new procedure 
the supreme court last year upheld the constitutionality of the 
guidelines 
some judges say the new system gives prosecutors too much power 
to coerce guilty pleas while stripping judges of authority to use 
discretion in sentencing 
