<TEXT>
a new lobbying group representing oilseed 
producers processors and users called wednesday for legislation to 
guarantee farmers a choice in what they produce under federal crop 
programs 
the oilseed council of america said genuine planting 
flexibility would help solve a decline in the competitiveness of 
the us oilseed industry oilseeds are led by soybeans but also 
include cottonseed sunflowers and canola 
lowell wilson of primghar iowa cochairman of the council 
said current commodity programs have dramatically reduced acreage 
planted to oilseeds by requiring producers to plant commodities 
supported by target prices to protect crop program base acreages 
used to compute benefits 
wilson said there is genuine planting flexibility when federal 
programs are neutral in their effect on farmers planting decisions 
according to a study released here by the council demand for 
protein meal and oil produced when oilseeds are crushed is growing 
at the rate of 4 percent a year world trade in oilseeds and their 
products the report said has increased twice as fast as trade in 
wheat and feed grains 
despite the growth the study reported that the us share of 
global oilseed production has dropped to 24 percent from 39 percent 
six years ago and that the us share of oilseed trade has 
declined to 45 percent from 75 percent 
floyd anderson of bismarck nd president of the national 
sunflowerseed association and cochairman of the council said 
planting flexibility would let farmers take advantage of the world 
demand for oilseeds by basing planting decisions on market 
situations as well as natural factors 
the formation of the group coincides with moves in congress to 
write new farm legislation to replace the 1985 law which expires 
at the end of the 1990 crop season 
but anderson said in a statement the council does not advocate 
any specific programs and that there are a number of policy 
approaches that will give producers genuine planting 
flexibility and continue farm income protection 
