deposed panamanian dictator manuel noriega is 
just another inmate with a window in his cell library and 
commissary privileges and standard cafeteria food at a federal 
prison officials say 
but he cannot come in contact with other inmates and must wear 
dark green coveralls not khaki to distinguish him as a security 
risk at the metropolitan correctional center in suburban miami 
noriega facing federal drug charges was held for three weeks 
in a basement apartment in the downtown federal courthouse before 
his move sunday 
hes just another inmate as far as were concerned said 
spokesman charles davis 
noriegas cell measures 86 square feet the same as the other 
cells but most other prisoners have roommates because of crowding 
in the pretrial detention center 
his cell is lighted with fluorescent bulbs and has a bed wool 
blanket chair writing table and a partition in front of the 
commode and sink writing paper is provided 
like other inmates noriega will be allowed to submit a list of 
potential visitors for approval by prison officials 
he and other inmates considered security risks are locked in 
their cells the entire day with the exception of an hour an hour 
and a half for showers and exercise davis said 
most prisoners eat three times a day in the prison cafeteria 
but guards pick noriegas meals from the standard fare and deliver 
them to his cell he is allowed to buy items from the commissary or 
check out library books but only from afar 
noriega can shower whenever he wants but the allotted five 
hours of outdoor exercise a week will be at varying times in a 
caged 20footby20foot yard 
a guard has been posted outside noriegas cell but no 
surveillance camera is used in the cell davis said a camera has 
been installed in a nearby interview room for meetings with 
attorneys or visitors 
defense attorney steven kollin wouldnt comment on the new 
living conditions but he renewed his contention that noriega is a 
prisoner of war who should be released to a third country 
a hearing on that claim is set for feb 8 before us district 
judge william hoeveler 
