which would require action by the states or cooperation by truck 
stops is part of an industry effort to identify and fire truckers 
who drink or use drugs while driving 
but donahue acknowleged at a news conference that the industry 
is trying to avoid the imposition of federal regulations mandating 
the use of expensive breathalyzers to detect alcohol consumption 
in comments filed wednesday with the department of 
transportation the association said that compelling all trucking 
companies to buy individual breathalyzers to test drivers could 
cost from 510 million to 850 million 
attaching breathalyzers to the ignition on each truck to prevent 
use of the vehicle if alcohol consumption was detected could cost 
close to 2 billion the association said 
donahue said alcohol and drug testing should be conducted during 
statemandated roadside checks 
blowing in an apparatus installed in the truck to see if you 
can drive doesnt make sense he said 
cost is a huge factor donahue said adding that alcohol and 
drug testing conducted solely by trucking companies would also 
prove to be a considerable administrative burden 
we want the roads safe thats good business good politics 
for us but we dont want it stupid 
the american people have the right to believe that the driver 
of an 80000 pound vehicle is sober donahue said adding that 
the 5 million truckers already are forbidden to drink or use drugs 
on the job or to have alcohol in their trucks 
it doesnt make sense to sell it to them he said about 
sales at truck stops its an unnecessary temptation to the 
drivers 
