distribution of this weeks edition of 
newsweek magazine has been delayed because a map depicts large 
parts of the jammukashmir region as pakistani territory a senior 
customs official said wednesday 
india and pakistan both claim jammukashmir the 43yearold 
dispute heated up again when india launched a crackdown jan 20 
against kashmiri moslems who want to secede from india 
the customs official speaking on condition of anonymity said 
the 10000 copies of newsweek that arrived at bombay airport early 
wednesday have not been impounded but he said a process often used 
to speed up clearance for weekly magazines is not being used to 
clear the newsweek issue 
normally consignments must be cleared against a bill of entry 
a procedure that can take up to two days in cases considered 
urgent the consignments are cleared faster with an understanding 
that bill of entry formalities will be completed later 
this is a facility extended in rare cases not as a matter of 
right but for convenience the customs official said 
in previous disputes over maps in foreign publications india 
has allowed the books or magazines in question to enter the country 
after stamping them with notations that the borders are neither 
correct nor authenticated 
there was no indication whether this would happen to the 
newsweek map 
newsweek is distributed in india by living media india ltd a 
