an american legion post is dropping its 
sponsorship of a bagpipe band after 42 years because a band member 
was a conscientious objector to the vietnam war 
charlie mcelwain 43 a seventh day baptist requested medical 
or noncombat duties instead of military service when he was 
drafted his draft board instead asked him to work two years at 
memorial general hospital in elkins 
american legion post 29 learned last year that mcelwain was a 
conscientious objector and in august asked him to withdraw from the 
27member west virginia highlander bagpipe band 
the state and national constitutions of the american legion 
say that no person can be associated with the american legion who 
has not offered himself to the military in an unqualified state 
said post 29 band committee chairman robert magos 
if you go in there and say i wont do this and i wont do 
that and i wont fight and i wont carry a gun then you do not 
qualify under the constitution of the american legion magos said 
i believe its discrimination against my religion and my 
freedoms as an american said mcelwain who said his ancestors 
came to this country in 1745 
the band marches in parades and has played at everything from 
funerals and weddings to the apple blossom festival in virginia 
