<TEXT>
president bushs 1991 budget came under 
renewed congressional attack on wednesday with critics brandishing 
figures that called into question 37 billion of the deficit 
reduction being claimed by the administration 
the analysis done by the bipartisan congressional budget 
office said that the deficit for next year without policy 
changes would total 138 billion not the 101 billion claimed by 
the administration 
cbo director robert d reischauer said that 26 billion of the 
higher deficit estimate was accounted for by using a less 
optimistic forecast on economic growth and interest rates the 
other 11 billion was attributed to higher projections on 
government spending in such areas as the savings and loan bailout 
and health care 
the growth forecast is critical to the governments revenue 
assumptions while the interest rate forecast affects estimates of 
how much the government will have to spend to finance the 28 
trillion national debt 
by using higher growth and lower interest rate assumptions than 
the cbo and most private economists the administration was able to 
come up with a starting deficit of 101 billion next year compared 
to the cbos 138 billion figure 
that means that the administration was only required to produce 
37 billion in savings to meet the legal requirement of proposing a 
budget with a 64 billion deficit in the 1991 budget year which 
starts next october 
by using the cbos assumptions which track the consensus 
forecast of private economists the administration would have had 
to double the amount of spending cuts or tax increases needed to 
meet the grammrudman deficit target 
house budget chairman leon panetta dcalif said that he could 
not remember such a wide disparity between the administrations 
economic assumptions and the cbo 
we are facing a terrible credibility problem with the american 
people on the base of these estimates panetta said 
congress is free to adopt either the cbo estimate or the 
assumptions in the bush budget in drawing up its own spending plan 
but the administrations economic assumptions are required to be 
used in determining whether acrosstheboard spending cuts will be 
triggered if the deficit is not reduced enough 
both budget director richard darman and michael boskin chairman 
of the presidents council of economic advisers were sharply 
questioned about the economic assumptions during separate 
appearances on thursday 
boskin appearing before the house budget committee said that 
the economy was going through a sluggish period at present with 
growth slumping to an anemic rate of just 05 percent in the final 
three months of 1990 but he predicted a rebound would occur in 
coming months 
he did not rule out however the possibility that growth as 
measured by the gross national product might dip below 1 percent 
in the current januarymarch quarter 
under the grammrudman law two consecutive quarters of growth 
below 1 percent would require lawmakers to vote on suspending the 
deficit reduction targets for 1991 
boskin said congress should not suspend the deficit targets 
especially if there were signals that growth was beginning to 
rebound because it could send a signal that the governments 
deficitfighting resolve was weakening 
a suspension of grammrudman could have very unfavorable 
impacts on financial markets and cause interest rates to rise he 
said 
darman testifying before the senate budget committee was 
hammered by democrats who described the budget as unrealistic in 
its economic assumptions and in its call for 292 billion for the 
military 
this is a menu of cold war leftovers and warmedover reagan 
said sen james sasser dtenn chairman of the committee 
im not at all sure we are going to get a budget agreement 
unless the rhetoric turns down said sen pete v domenici of new 
mexico senior republican on the panel 
darman denied the budget ignores the movement toward democracy 
in eastern europe which many lawmakers view as requiring less 
military spending the reality is that this is a budget which 
proposes a 26 percent real cut in military spending in the first 
year and a 2 percent real cut every year thereafter he said 
i do not regard this as a serious budget said sen bennett 
johnston dla he asked darman when do we get down to the 
serious business of getting together with the white house and 
negotiating a compromise 
wed be prepared to start at 10 oclock tonight after the 
presidents speech darman replied referring to bushs state of 
the union address 
