<TEXT>
state lawmakers decided tuesday not to vote 
on a measure to repeal unenforceable criminal penalties for doctors 
who perform abortions but they continued debate on a bill to 
require minors to get permission for abortions 
the assembly voted 5739 to keep the repeal bill in the 
amendment stage and not bring it to the floor for a final vote a 
move that prochoice lawmakers said effectively killed the measure 
its dead rep rebecca young a democrat said minutes 
after the vote this is the end of the bill for this session 
the bill would have repealed an outdated state law that provides 
criminal penalties including prison terms for doctors who perform 
abortions the law has been unenforceable since a 1973 us supreme 
court ruling legalized abortion nationwide 
abortionrights lawmakers said they want to remove the law from 
the books in case the high court should overturn roe vs wade 
abortion opponents said the law should be kept for the same reason 
the second bill backed by abortion opponents would require 
minors to obtain permission from at least one parent or a court 
order before having an abortion 
if the second bill is approved by the assembly it would require 
approval by the senate and gov tommy g thompson before becoming 
law 
rep david clarenbach a prochoice democrat said he had 
expected the repeal bill to be set back tuesday but predicted it 
would pass some day 
this legislature is in the process of becoming prochoice 
he said today many of you are risking your political careers by 
failing to take a prochoice stand 
assembly speaker thomas loftus also a democrat said the repeal 
measure is not dead and could be brought up again later this week 
if twothirds of the assembly voted to do so 
you have to live with these votes for the rest of your 
political life loftus had said earlier 
before deciding not to vote on the repeal bill the assembly 
rejected an amendment by democratic rep thomas seery to alter the 
measure so that doctors who performed abortions and women who 
obtained abortions after the 18th week of pregnancy could still 
face criminal penalties 
what im trying to do is find a middle ground seery said 
what im trying to do is determine when life begins 
lawmakers scrambled tuesday before the floor session began to 
introduce amendments to the second bill which would require minors 
to get permission before having an abortion 
some of the estimated 21 amendments hadnt even been drafted 
shortly before the 99member assembly began debate tuesday 
afternoon by 9 pm the assembly had acted only two of the 
amendments increasing chances that the session would go into 
wednesday 
the proposals include provisions to require teenagers to obtain 
the consent of one parent before carrying a child to full term and 
to require parents of teenage mothers to support their 
grandchildren 
