<TEXT>
if communists had a heaven it might look 
like bologna 
orange buses glide through a huge historic district closed to 
other traffic senior citizens take governmentsubsidized vacations 
on the riviera half the citys youngsters attend lowcost daycare 
centers 
the red disneyland as the italian press calls it has long 
been considered the showcase of communism italianstyle so when 
the government recently suggested turning city services over to 
private enterprise it left many italians in shock 
the proposal coming from bologna is in some measure 
revolutionary columnist miriam mafai wrote in the national 
newspaper la repubblica 
all previous ideas are being erased from the slate not only 
for the italian communist party but for all the left 
the proposal put forth for the northern italian city is 
considered symbolic of the new directions being pursued by the 
italys national communist party the largest in the west as it 
seeks to overcome an electoral decline and the specter of communist 
failure in eastern europe 
i dont want to be reduced to a souvenir of a past era said 
bolognas 45yearold mayor renzo imbeni an energetic marxist 
with a bushy black mustache 
i want to be here when the history of tomorrow is written the 
change stems from this need 
with a population of 417000 bologna is the biggest city in the 
italian red belt a communistgoverned region that has become 
one of the countrys wealthiest areas 
after world war ii when voters turned to the party that helped 
lead the antifascist resistance bologna became italys first 
large city to elect a communist administration 
it earned national fame for its doitall governments which 
set up pharmacies in poor neighborhoods paid the rent for 
lowincome elderly citizens and offered free bus transportation 
during rush hours 
when buildings decayed in the porticolined historic district 
the government spent millions of dollars to restore them then 
moved the workingclass residents back in 
to help women work it set up a daycare system that even today 
charges the equivalent of only 65 to 150 a month for children up 
to 5 
there is a rather high level of social protection mayor 
imbeni said in an interview in the communal palace a 15thcentury 
building surrounded by bulletin boards featuring the communist 
daily newspaper lunita 
but its not written anywhere that we will be able to 
guarantee this also in the future 
he noted that the welfarestate system had deteriorated in many 
countries due to stagnant revenues an increase in the number of 
needy and a shrinking pool of young people all problems in 
bologna 
because of this the choice was made for a requalification 
and a renewal of the welfare state we have locally imbeni said 
what bologna is proposing to do is sell off its slaughterhouse 
and 21 city pharmacies and transfer such services as the cleaning 
of schools provision of student lunches and street maintenance to 
a mixed publicprivate concern it also is discussing private 
management of the hundreds of cityowned offices and apartments 
the money saved would be devoted to priority areas such as the 
increasing number of elderly and third world immigrants and the 
environment 
the plan has won praise from business executives average 
citizens and the national communist party which is italys 
secondbiggest party the main critics are rival political parties 
which charge the project is merely a maneuver to win votes in 
municipal elections this coming may 
if its real and concrete this is an interesting stunning 
new initiative an initiative that will be taken as an example by 
other city governments said gianandrea rocco di torrepadula 
head of the local industrialists association 
in comparison to other cities this one is run ok said 
marco bassi 46 who owns a newsstand in the workingclass little 
bologna neighborhood but things always go better in the private 
sector 
imbeni insists that the communists are not doing an aboutface 
people say the concept of state ownership is part of the 
communist culture he said but for the communists of bologna 
this isnt true and for the italian communists that was years 
ago 
indeed bologna and the rest of the red belt are known for 
their citizens entrepreneurial spirit illustrated by the network 
of cooperatives most linked to the communists which do 
everything from producing parmesan cheese to running restaurants 
the national communist party is hailing the bologna plan an 
example of its own new course the party has long embraced 
parliamentary democracy but has been kept out of the government for 
four decades 
in line with its new program the party has called an 
extraordinary congress for march to decide whether to become a new 
leftist umbrella group and perhaps even drop the communist name 
and hammerandsickle symbol 
while the bologna proposal was described as a revolution in 
national newspapers it will leave many city services intact 
the government refuses to privatize the daycare system and the 
vast bus network although it has abolished the free rushhour 
rides 
the lowincome elderly will still have a taxi service domestic 
helpers 32 social centers and subsidized vacations on the italian 
riviera 
the government will also continue to provide lowcost study 
vacations for teens in england and on the french riviera 
we dont want to change because theres a black spot on the 
soul of our past imbeni said we must change because we want 
to be here in the year 2000 with the name we have today or 
another i want to be here 
</TEXT>
