<TEXT>
the american dental association scoffed at a 
recent study that found highly fluoridated water caused a rare form 
of bone cancer in some rats and reaffirmed its support of the 
anticavity treatment 
it is totally inappropriate to draw any conclusions from this 
single study or to suggest that it is applicable to human beings 
said dr enid neidle director of scientific affairs for the ada 
one rat among a group of 50 developed bone cancer after 
consuming fluoridated water in a concentration of 45 parts per 
million over two years according to preliminary data from a study 
conducted by the national toxicology program 
four rats in another group developed the cancer after drinking 
fluoridated water with a concentration of 79 parts per million over 
the same period the study found 
but the chicagobased ada said tuesday the public should not 
fear sodium fluoride because humans ingest much smaller amounts of 
the chemical 
the average person drinks about eight glasses of water a day 
the ada said in a press release a person would have to drink 380 
glasses each day to obtain the same concentration of fluoride as 
that in the first group of rats and about 700 glasses a day to 
obtain the same concentration of fluoride as that in the second 
group of rats the association said 
fluoride a natural chemical that appears in some waterways has 
remained a controversial issue for many american communities since 
1945 when it was artificially introduced into the public water 
supply in grand rapids mich and newburgh ny 
people who favor fluoridation as the best way to prevent tooth 
decay say it prevents about twothirds of all cavities and is 
almost completely safe 
those who oppose the fluoridation process say the treated water 
stains teeth could harm bones and may cause certain forms of 
cancer 
public water systems in the united states last year served about 
213 million people but only 61 percent of them drink fluoridated 
water in 1989 los angeles san francisco portland ore and san 
antonio still were without fluoridated water according to the 
national institute of dental research 
many other local and state governments require fluoridation by 
law 
