<TEXT>
much of prince william sound remains 
polluted from the nations worst oil spill and the cleanup must 
resume when the weather improves this spring gov steve cowper 
said wednesday 
about 117 miles of shore throughout the sound remain oiled from 
the exxon valdez spill including 85 heavily oiled areas according 
to a state survey released by cowper while much of the surface oil 
is gone in 224 locations oil was found up to 28 inches deep in the 
rocky beaches he said 
the evidence is that the problem will not go away by the end 
of this winter and that we are going to have to return to the 
beaches of coastal alaska to clean up this mess cowper told a 
news conference 
he also called on congress to pass pending legislation that 
would require oil tankers using us ports to have double hulls and 
double bottoms within several years 
nearly 11 million gallons of north slope crude gushed from the 
valdez after it ran aground march 24 
the state department of environmental conservation surveyed the 
shores in october and november after exxon corp halted its cleanup 
due to severe winter weather the data took some time to assemble 
state officials said and the survey was not completed until last 
week 
the news conference came as jury selection was under way in 
anchorage in the criminal trial of joseph hazelwood former captain 
of the exxon valdez cowper spokesman david ramseur said reporters 
covering the trial were invited to take part in the news conference 
by telephone 
exxon officials did not dispute the surveys findings but said 
nature has removed oil from many shores since the information was 
collected last fall 
we know that in the highenergy areas that the winter storms 
are having a dramatic effect said don carpenter exxons 
operations and logistics manager in anchorage the 32 miles in 
the sheltered areas we have more concern about but theres 
evidence that the effect of natures forces is dramatic there 
too 
but recent spot checks found continued heavy oil accumulations 
cowper said showing reporters a twominute video with scenes of 
oiled beaches shot in the past three days the scenes confirm the 
fall surveys results he said 
the reason why we are presenting this beach survey is not to 
criticize the efforts that have been made so far he said the 
point is to show the amount of work that has to be done as soon as 
the weather clears 
exxon and several government agencies will put together a spring 
cleanup plan after another survey is conducted in april exxon 
spokesman perry smith said a determination of what cleanup 
measures if any are needed will be made by may 
cowper said his administration decided to support the proposed 
requirement for doublebottomed doublehulled tankers despite the 
estimated 10 million a year it would cost the state in reduced oil 
revenues 
the industrys cost of upgrading the alaska tanker fleet is a 
transportation expense that would be deducted from the wellhead 
price of alaska oil on which the state bases its taxes and 
royalties 
we think that its worth it cowper said 
the tankers used in the alaska trade are aging and will have to 
replaced eventually anyway he said 
a coast guard study estimated the exxon valdez would have 
released about 60 percent less oil if it had a double bottom 
