<TEXT>
snow blanketed much of japan and south korea on 
thursday snarling transportation and leaving more than two dozen 
people dead and hundreds injured this week officials said 
tokyo a city unused to anything more than a dusting of snow 
woke up to find nearly 3 inches on the ground and more falling by 
dawn more than 3 inches had fallen in adjacent yokohama and 7 
inches in mito 63 miles northeast of tokyo the meteorological 
agency said 
in south korea about 10 inches of snow fell by early thursday in 
seoul the capital city of 10 million people 
police reported hundreds of casualties in snowrelated traffic 
accidents including 27 deaths on tuesday when snow began piling 
up damage was estimated at 6 million nationwide 
villages along the east coast and nearby mountains were hit 
hardest with up to 5 feet of snow since tuesday afternoon 
the international airport at narita 35 miles northeast of 
tokyo was closed at 800 am for snow removal but was scheduled 
to reopen about an hour later 
at tokyos haneda airport 43 domestic flights were canceled due 
to snow affecting 5000 passengers kyodo news service reported 
another domestic airport at sendai in northwestern japan was 
also closed due to snow kyodo said 
in tokyo 18 people were slightly injured after they fell on 
slippery roads or were involved in snowrelated traffic accidents 
said sabuto nakane a spokesman for the tokyo fire department 
there were no reports of deaths or injuries elsewhere 
meanwhile the bullet trains were running at a reduced 106 mph 
due to snow railway officials said the intercity trains usually 
run at 130 mph 
about 40000 government officials and police were ordered out 
thursday to clear korean streets of snow and open traffic to 
isolated villages after forecasters lifted snow warnings officials 
said 
