<TEXT>
largescale us troop cuts in europe at the 
level president bush discussed with soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev wednesday would deal an economic blow to west germany 
bush proposed that us and soviet troops be reduced to 195000 
officials in washington said and he was to announce the plan 
formally in his state of the union address before a joint session 
of congress wednesday night 
bushs proposal was described by the officials who spoke on 
condition of anonymity as a result of the collapse of hardline 
communist governments in eastern europe 
the plan would cover more than 265000 us troops in western 
europe and 565000 soviet forces in central and eastern europe 
about 250000 us servicemen are based in west germany alone 
there was no immediate reaction from west german officials to 
bushs plan 
foreign ministry spokesman rainer mueller said in bonn that 
details of the bush proposal were not yet available and that they 
would have to be studied by highlevel officials before any comment 
could be made on the plan 
latenight television newscasts reported briefly without 
comment that bush was expected to call for deeper troop cuts 
the colognebased german economics institute reported in a july 
study that west germany earns 5 billion a year from us military 
expenditures it warned that a troop pullout would mean economic 
collapse for regions that are heavily dependent on the american 
presence 
an extensive analysis of the us bases was undertaken because 
of the growing public tendency to see american troops as a burden 
institute director for economic and scientific affairs otto vogel 
said at the time 
there has been increasing support in recent months for troop 
cuts as a way to reduce tensions in europe and move the german 
states closer to reunification now that the communists in east 
germany no longer have a monopoly on power 
east germany is the kremlins most critical military ally and 
about 400000 soviet troops are stationed in the country 
the kremlin does not want to lose its frontline bases in east 
germany but it has indicated it could accept a neutral state 
west germany is under pressure to remain in nato and keep troops 
as part of its commitment to the western defense alliance the 
troops however are an obstacle to reunification 
last may bush proposed a 275000 ceiling on us and on soviet 
forces and said negotiations to reach that goal should be wrapped 
up within a year 
before now bush has said he would not support further cuts 
until the current talks were wrapped up but a senior 
administration official said events were running ahead of the 
negotiations 
west german foreign minister hansdietrich genscher said on 
wednesday that a reunited germany could stay loyal to nato without 
drawing the territory now comprising a crucial moscow ally into the 
western military alliance 
genscher outlined in a speech to the evangelical institute in 
tutzing near munich what he sees as a security guarantee for 
moscow and a compromise that could also assuage the united states 
the foreign minister suggested that the territory now 
constituting west germany could remain in the north atlantic treaty 
organization while the area east of the elbe river east germany 
would not contain military facilities 
us and west european allies have indicated they would accept 
reunification as long as germany stays within nato 
