<TEXT>
american churches which largely lost their free 
publicservice television outlets on networks when broadcasting was 
deregulated now have a fastgrowing network of their own 
they had been virtually silenced in that powerful medium as 
national channels began selling time to moneysoliciting 
televangelists some of whose lapses tainted religion itself 
but the major faith groups protestant roman catholic eastern 
orthodox jewish and mormon have teamed up in developing a cable 
network that in its first year has more than doubled its reach 
visn standing for vision interfaith satellite network is now 
distributed on 38l cable systems across the nation some serving 
several communities and reaching 7 million households up from 3 
million at the outset 
it also has more than tripled its programming time on the air 
from five hours to 18 hours daily 
one of the things weve had going for us is the terrific cable 
network interest in the breadth of sponsoring religious groups 
says jeff weber the networks executive vice president 
the main religious denominations had virtually been left out 
in the cold by the profusion of contributionsseeking individual 
preachers buying commercial time but the new network is 
counterbalancing that scene 
our programs are for faith groups that represent the broad 
concerns and interests of the american people he added in an 
interview the way were geared up gives them an opportunity to 
use tv in ways not done before 
a wide variety of valuesoriented programs are offered dramas 
magazinestyle shows on various issues problem counseling select 
movies with discussion before an after callin talk shows 
religious news documentaries and others 
also included are cartoons and other childrens programs and 
even a couple of comedy series about bumbling and silliness within 
the religious fold 
the last thing the network wants to be is heavyhanded 
weber said theres plenty of room for laughter in heaven 
the network prohibits proselytizing for particular denominations 
or soliciting funds that has been abused in the past weber 
said were not in the business of taking money out of the local 
church 
the rev wilford v bane jr of nashville tenn a united 
methodist and the networks general manager and president said 
we want to stimulate people to get involved in their own 
communities 
however he said we can provide a perhaps larger perspective 
and put faith in a context beyond local experience tv can add 
dimensions that challenge folks 
he recited a list of renowned religious thinkers who have 
appeared on shows discussing such questions as who is god who is 
jesus what does prayer mean why evil and added 
persons of that stature talking in ones living room about 
questions of that depth certainly adds a dimension to peoples 
religious experience 
the coalition of 22 denominations owning the yearold network 
includes most major us religious bodies episcopal lutheran 
jewish presbyterian american baptist methodist roman catholic 
greek orthodox and mormon 
smaller groups such as the mennonites moravians seventhday 
adventists and salvation army also are participants 
weber 42 a presbyterian layman who previously worked in 
commercial television said we want to reach people who wouldnt 
watch the typical tv religion fare which offers prepackaged answers 
we want to help focus on the questions themselves there are a 
variety of ways of doing it dramas documentaries callin shows 
profiles of characters dealing with the kinds of questions that 
are being asked 
we want to help people in their own struggle with questions of 
faith 
but the fare also entertains particularly the dramas and music 
about half the programs are produced by participating 
denominations including some worship services but mostly different 
kinds of shows the other half obtained from other producers in 
this country and abroad 
denominations pay costs of their own productions supplying them 
free to the network which thus is able to operate on a relative 
small central budget of about 6 million annually most of it for 
satellite transmission 
about a third of this a steadily growing proportion now is 
covered by fees from cable systems the rest in subsidized funding 
from the cable industry guaranteed through the next two years and 
renewable 
by that time the network expects to be doubled again in size 
reaching more than 15 million homes and selfsupporting it is 
beginning to sell selective advertising but that source still is 
minimal weber said 
the network with a small central staff of 15 operates at 
studios in trinity church in downtown manhattan 
bane said the varied programming sparks religious concern 
sometimes in almost invisible ways and should help bring a 
resurgence of judeochristian values back into mainstream 
thinking 
added weber the timing is right the decade of the 90s is 
going to see a turning back to faith in meaningful ways 
</TEXT>
