<TEXT>
would you really like to see zero inflation 
a lot of people would including alan greenspan chairman of the 
federal reserve board and at least one president of a federal 
reserve bank w lee hoskins of cleveland 
these are knowledgeable people with as much power as anyone to 
see that their views are accomplished already they are in pursuit 
of those goals 
also of that mind are some academic theoreticians lots of 
business people and some folks in the financial community where 
inflation or its threat is considered an enemy to securities 
many ordinary folks might like it too retirees enjoy knowing 
their pension wont be eroded savers want assurance that their 
money wont diminish in buying power workers want raises to mean 
something 
many people would like to see inflation disappear simply because 
they have come to think of it as evil sinful deceitful 
destructive a killjoy that ruins the party repeatedly it is so 
described in the media 
in all inflation is about the most popular enemy in economics 
with very few people having anything good to say about it to 
support it or defend it is likely to ruin anyones reputation for 
common sense 
yet in the past 60 years inflation generally has been 
accompanied by economic growth while its absence has almost always 
been associated with recession or depression 
true some of that growth is an illusion with rising prices 
shaving from buying power almost as much or more than is added to 
paychecks thats one of the raps against inflation it is 
deceptive 
it is also well known and documented that high or rising 
inflation is often a prelude to recession even a cause and most 
certainly a reflection of unsustainable growth rates 
using as measuring sticks the 1982 dollar and the socalled 
gross national product deflator the most broadbased inflation 
index only in 1936 did inflation average exactly zero for the year 
while that was in the midst of the great depression it was one 
of the better years within it gnp grew sharply only to fall again 
in 1938 in most years of the great depression however there was 
no inflation whatever 
in fact you might say deflation ran wild the worst of it was 
in 1932 when inflation reached minus 115 percent but it was 
also evident in every year from 1930 through 1934 and again in 
1938 and 1939 
in 1949 the inflationdeflation rate dipped below zero again 
to 04 percent and while the economy didnt shrink it also failed 
to grow since then there has always been at least 1 percent 
inflation the least being in 1961 
this record it can be argued might add up to nothing still 
it is hard to dispute the empirical evidence that the pursuit of 
zero inflation may be dangerous 
theory bolsters the contention for example proponents and 
opponents of the zeroinflation goal agree that to bring down any 
existing level of inflation means slowing economic expansion 
any slowdown of course is reflected in and demonstrated by 
statistical evidence of curtailed production sales profits wages 
and layoffs and perhaps in lower corporate stock prices and 
dividends too 
an intentionally induced slowdown implemented by restraining 
money supply and keeping interest rates high is a fragile 
undertaking at best it is probably mere guesswork as to when to 
apply or relieve pressure 
during this time the fed must rely on statistical measurements 
and some of those measurements provide evidence after the fact 
when they reveal their news it is already too late to seek zero 
therefore is to risk recession 
there is also error to contend with 
each year economist walter j williams surveys his colleagues 
at a meeting of the national association of business economists 
last year he found 72 percent of them were unhappy with the quality 
of government data 
it is worth noting he said and perhaps a little 
frightening that the greatest skepticism was directed at numbers 
generally given the most weight by financial decisionmakers 
among them are reports on the gross national product whose 
expansion or shrinkage determines whether we are in recession 
</TEXT>
