<TEXT>
theres a story that claude monet began his 
series paintings because the light was changing so fast on a 
grain stack he was painting that he kept asking his stepdaughter to 
run for more canvases 
its a kind of wonderful and amusing but completely fallacious 
tale said paul h tucker associate professor of art at the 
university of massachusetts at boston and guest curator of monet 
in the 90s the series paintings which opens at the museum of 
fine arts on wednesday 
monet the leading french impressionist is known to have done 
218 series paintings all but 12 during the 1890s when he was 
in his 50s 
he chose 16 subjects some for their historical or cultural 
significance among the works were 30 paintings each of grain 
stacks and the rouen cathedral 24 paintings of poplars and 18 of 
the japanese bridge over his waterlily garden at giverny 
there are 86 in the exhibition more than twice the number monet 
ever showed at one time the works have been loaned from all over 
the world including leningrad paris tokyo and boston 
this is the largest of all the series ever assembled said 
tucker 
why monet painted series is not absolutely certain he said but 
the monet specialist thinks one reason was to show the wideranging 
effects of nature 
another was to answer the challenges posed by younger artists 
especially georges seurat whose a sunday on the island of the 
grande jatte in 1886 was an enormous challenge to impressionism 
it was an assault tucker said 
monet responded to the challenges with the revolutionary idea of 
doing a series of paintings on the same subject 
he carved out a completely new niche it was very 
inventive very daring tucker said 
monet painted his subjects in different seasons at different 
times of day sometimes from different angles 
one of the wonders of the show is to be able to compare and 
contrast tucker said the style differs for almost every series 
as well in terms of color composition and the way the paint was 
applied 
the series paintings were a way for him to assert the 
continued vitality of impressionism tucker said 
the repeating images responded to the repetitiousness in 
seurats style of painting with dots while retaining an 
individualism monet believed was lacking in seurats work tucker 
said 
though the approach and style were revolutionary they were not 
monets sole concern he wants us in the end to be more attuned 
to nature as well tucker said 
not one of the series is intact in a single collection although 
statesman georges clemenceau urged the president of france to buy 
all the rouen cathedral paintings for the country 
the most important thing was to sell said tucker and some 
paintings from a series were sold before the series was exhibited 
im sure monet would have been thrilled if an individual 
collector bought them all but he wanted to have them sold he 
probably had a big mortgage too 
tucker wrote the text more a book than a catalog that 
accompanies the exhibit he began research for a book on monets 
series paintings six years ago while on a sabbatical and in 
talking with people at the museum of fine arts an exhibit of the 
paintings was suggested 
