<TEXT>
when doris kearns goodwin was writing her 
history of the fitzgeralds and the kennedys she was often only a 
few chapters ahead of the screenwriter for the miniseries the 
kennedys of massachusetts 
goodwins book the fitzgeralds and the kennedys traces the 
personal and political histories of the two families from their 
irish roots to boston to the election of john f kennedy as 
president 
the sixhour miniseries will be broadcast by abc on sunday 
monday and tuesday starring william peterson as joe kennedy 
annette otoole as rose fitzgerald kennedy pat hingle as joes 
father pj kennedy charles durning as roses father john 
honey fitz fitzgerald steven weber as john f kennedy and 
madolyn smithosborne as actress gloria swanson joe kennedys 
longtime mistress 
the authors 13yearold son michael goodwin plays joe jr 
the book was bought as a miniseries in 1982 in the early stages 
of the manuscript and screenwriter william hanley working chapter 
by chapter frequently called goodwin to see what was coming next 
doing the research was the best part said goodwin a former 
harvard professor whos now working on a book about the american 
homefront in world war ii with franklin and eleanor roosevelt as 
the focus it also has been sold as a miniseries 
it was wonderful to find things that give you the feel and 
texture of the era she said when i learn something i become 
very excited to get it out to the reader honey fitz spent a year 
at the harvard medical school and i became so fascinated with 
medicine of that period that the publisher had to tell me to cut it 
out 
the book began as a traditional biography of president kennedy 
goodwins husband richard goodwin had been a speechwriter for 
kennedy and she had been a special assistant to president johnson 
and wrote lyndon johnson and the american dream 
it took on a new dimension when she began her research one of 
the great treasures she found were 150 cartons of papers saved by 
joe and rose kennedy they were at the kennedy library but no one 
had looked at them and they had not yet been deeded to the library 
she obtained permission from sen edward m kennedy to go through 
the material 
that took a year and a half goodwin said they had saved 
every letter every report card every piece of paper even gloria 
swansons income tax statements those letters told me the internal 
dynamics of the family and enabled hanley to write their dialogue 
the papers fell into the boxes as they would fall in life you 
could see how each event related to another 
asked what set the fitzgeralds and the kennedys apart from 
millions of other irish catholics goodwin said the fitzgeralds 
and particularly joe kennedy instilled into their kids that above 
all else they were a family they presented themselves to the world 
like a clan they had traditions and loyalties and rituals the 
kids knew they had to be there for dinner every night they knew 
they went to hyannisport on a certain day 
second part of the family ethos was that they lived on the 
edge you create your own success and if the family backs you it 
doesnt matter what the world thinks 
joe kennedy despite his failings gave the family a center she 
said he drove himself and his family relentlessly to succeed 
partly because of the exclusion he had felt in boston as an irish 
catholic 
the miniseries filmed largely in boston evokes a strong 
feeling for the period it captures often through banter the 
fierce loyalties and competition within the families 
the original screenplay began in ireland and ran for 11 hours 
but it was cut to six hours and now begins when honey fitz 
already is mayor of boston like the book it ends with kennedys 
election to the presidency 
after goodwin completed the book she wasnt sure how the 
kennedys would feel since it exposes many family secrets 
there are many times in the book when you feel anger toward 
joe or rose she said i wasnt trying to judge them i heard 
the family was upset at first 
normally the kennedys dont read books about them but there 
was so much history about the fitzgeralds that no one knew that 
theybegan to read the book then i received 12 copies of the book 
from sargent shriver eunices husband he wanted them signed for 
the kids in general they seemed to like the book i think theyll 
feel the same way about the miniseries 
</TEXT>
