<TEXT>
a house panel looking into the biggest 
bankruptcy filing in retail history got an earful about the dangers 
of leveraged buyouts and the panels chief said urged new 
restrictions to prevent potential takeover trophies from 
becoming bankruptcy debtors 
witnesses ranging from the massachusetts attorney general to the 
head of the union representing bloomingdales workers testified 
tuesday about the problems facing federated department stores inc 
and allied stores corp 
the two retailing giants have filed for bankruptcy 
reorganization because of their inability to finance debts taken on 
when campeau corp acquired the companies in the 1980s 
the groundwork for todays fiasco was laid by the reagan 
administration which took a handsoff view of antitrust 
enforcement said massachusetts attorney general james m shannon 
rep jack brooks chairman of the house judiciary committees 
economic and commercial law subcommittee echoed that complaint 
criticizing the anything goes regulators of the past decade 
brooks dtexas warned that if the white house doesnt act to 
rein in debtfinanced takeovers such as leveraged buyouts then 
congress must take the initiative by considering antitrust 
bankruptcy and tax legislation to stop the lbo frenzy 
brooks said the chapter 11 filing by the campeau subsidiaries 
may have signaled that the takeover trophies of the 1980s will 
soon become the bankruptcy debtors of the 1990s 
torontobased campeau amassed 75 billion in debt acquiring 
allied and federated largely through loans and junk bonds 
allied and federated both headquartered in cincinnati ohio 
operate such well known chains as bloomingdales jordan marsh the 
bon marche and lazarus without the burden of their buyout debt 
they would be profitable healthy businesses 
the subcommittees ranking republican rep hamilton fish jr 
of new york said congress should carefully review any tax 
advantages or incentives that encourage the use of the lbo 
mechanism 
fish said the campeau situation pointed out an important flaw 
in the corporate tax code it is cheaper for a business to borrow 
money through a leveraged buyout than it is to raise the necessary 
funds by the more traditional issuance of stock 
in a leveraged buyout a companys buyers put up its assets as 
collateral to secure financing they hope to finance the debt with 
the target companys cash flow and by selling off some operations 
interest on that debt in most cases is tax deductible making such 
deals attractive to the buyers 
since campeau took over federated an estimated 10000 jobs 
have been lost with 400 positions eliminated at bloomingdales 
alone said lenore miller president of the retail wholesale and 
department store union which represents 4000 bloomingdales 
employees 
shannon of massachusetts said campeaus problems would have been 
greater if he and other state attorneys general hadnt taken action 
on campeaus federated takeover 
he said the two main department stores in his region jordan 
marsh and filenes would have become campeau properties if the 
state officials hadnt acted campeau already had jordan marsh as 
part of the allied operation while federated owned filenes 
by law the federal trade commission was responsible for 
reviewing this proposal at the federal level but despite our 
urging the commission allowed the merger to go through without 
even giving it an extended review said shannon 
he said campeau agreed to relinquish filenes after he and 
attorneys general in maine new hampshire and new york threatened 
to oppose campeaus acquisition of federated 
shannon said the bush administration unlike its predecessor 
has shown signs that it intends to be more active in merger 
enforcement 
we have not seen or heard his testimony and we really cant 
comment said susan ticknor a spokeswoman with for ftc 
but two professors said the antitrust laws may be 
insufficient to cope with the deal mania sweeping corporate 
america 
walter adams past president of michaigan state university and 
james w brock professor of economics at ohios miami university 
suggested requiring those behind large mergers or buyouts 1 
billion or more to file a public impact statement to demonstrate 
that the deal is in the national interest 
</TEXT>
