<TEXT>
grab your wallets democrats in congress 
think they have received a signal from president bush on how much 
he would be willing to accept in tax increases this year 
the magic number is 217 billion the total for the hodgepodge 
of tax increases user fees and asset sales that bush included in 
his 1991 spending plan 
democrats say they believe the 217 billion represents the 
amount in higher revenues the administration would be willing to 
accept during budget negotiations this year 
both senate budget committee chairman james sasser dtenn and 
house budget committee chairman leon panetta dcalif told 
reporters they were satisfied with bushs new revenue total but 
they indicated they would radically alter the way the money was 
raised 
that revenue figure in total is something that we can accept 
unfortunately in bushs budget it is not legitimately obtained 
sasser said 
critics of the budget questioned for instance bushs claim 
that he would be able to push tax collections up by 25 billion in 
1991 through management reforms at the internal revenue service 
at the center of the tax debate will be the administrations 
renewed push to cut the tax on capital gains which critics charge 
would benefit the wealthy and a rival plan by sen daniel 
moynihan dny to trim social security payroll taxes by 62 
billion over the next two years 
treasury secretary nicholas brady on tuesday rejected the idea 
that the administration might be willing to support moynihans 
proposal or at least a scaleddown version in exchange for 
democrats dropping their opposition to the capital gains reduction 
brady termed moynihans proposal goofy and the height of 
folly because it would raise doubts in americans minds about the 
safety of the social security trust funds 
sasser said the administration was not being consistent when it 
attacked moynihans proposal as a revenueloser while pushing a 
capital gains tax cut that benefits the wealthy and loses huge 
blocks of revenue in the years ahead 
but for 1991 the administrations budget shows the capital 
gains tax cut is a revenuegainer in fact it would account for 
the single biggest jump in tax revenues in the presidents budget 
an increase of 49 billion 
the higher figure is based on a belief that investors would rush 
to sell assets such as stocks or real estate to take advantage of 
the lower tax rate but critics charge the lower rate would result 
in a loss to the treasury in later years 
in all the bush budget proposes 157 billion in new tax 
revenues which would be offset by 18 billion in proposed cuts 
including an estimated 200 million loss in the first year from 
implementation of bushs proposed family savings accounts offering 
taxpayers to put away up to 5000 annually in taxfree accounts 
in addition the president proposes raising 56 billion in new 
user fees charged for providing government services 16 billion 
in the sale of government assets and 600 million in other new 
receipts bringing the total to 217 billion 
critics charged that bush recycled a variety of proposals some 
dating back to the early reagan years that congress has repeatedly 
rejected 
one retread is a measure to assess federal social security taxes 
on state and local government employees in the handful of states 
who are not now covered by the levy a 38 billion revenue raiser 
that bush unsuccessfully sought last year 
panetta suggested that congress might consider compromising on 
the capital gains cut sought by bush if the president was willing 
to consider tax increases in other areas possibly a higher top tax 
rate for individuals or a boost in energy taxes 
