the value of takeovers involving us companies 
that make computer software or offer other computer services fell 
18 percent in 1989 according to a report wednesday from an 
investment bank that tracks the industry 
despite last years drop to 73 billion from 1988s 
extraordinary 89 billion in mergers last years figure was 49 
percent above the previous record year of 1987 that year the 
value of such deals totaled 49 billion 
the report was compiled by broadview associates of fort lee 
nj a leading investment banker in the computer services 
industry on behalf of adapso the computer services and software 
industry association based in arlington va 
this year 1989 we saw a strong shift from deals over 100 
million to middlemarket transactions in the 20 million to 100 
million range said broadview partner harvey l poppel 
the surge in middlemarket transactions has been fueled by the 
mounting reluctance of underwriters to take mediumsized firms 
public he said since such firms typically need additional 
resources to achieve critical economies of scale and scope 
acquisition has emerged as a preferred route 
another reason for the falloff in the value of deals last year 
is that the recent earnings volatility of many public computer 
software and hardware companies has scared off buyers from outside 
the industry said charles federman another broadview partner 
the report covers companies offering software products computer 
systems integration equipment and professional services processing 
and networkbased data services training and maintenance 
