<TEXT>
the resignation of peter a cohen as head of 
shearson lehman hutton inc the nations secondlargest brokerage 
capped a career that personified wall streets noholdsbarred 
expansion in the 1980s as well as its recent decline 
cohen chairman and chief executive officer of shearson quit 
tuesday amid turmoil at a firm that grew from a mediumsized retail 
brokerage into one of the nations most powerful investment houses 
under his leadership 
shearson today announced a plan to raise about 250 million by 
offering stock to existing shareholders it replaces a public 
offering scrapped because of the firms slumping stock price and 
cohens resignation 
under the plan parent american express co would cut its stake 
in shearson to about 45 percent fulfilling a longtime goal of 
dropping the brokerage from its balance sheet 
after rising 75 cents tuesday shearson stock gained 50 cents to 
1175 this morning in new york stock exchange trading 
cohens departure culminated a shakeup of senior management in 
recent months brought on by the tough times facing the securities 
industry 
late last year thenshearson president jeffrey b lane left the 
firm after he was demoted as part of a series of moves instituted 
by his longtime sidekick cohen 
they put it together basically said lawrence eckenfelder 
an analyst with prudentialbache securities inc in san francisco 
much of the growth and expansion in the 80s was peter and jeff 
but shearson like other major wall stree firms has suffered 
because of a slowdown in business since the october 1987 market 
crash many analysts believe the firm expanded too far too fast and 
now is paying the price 
shearson late last year slashed 800 jobs cut broker 
commissions implemented the senior management shakeup and embarked 
on the recapitalization plan designed to raise about 865 million 
shearson last week reported 1989 profits of 110 million up 
from 96 million a year earlier but a third of the profits came 
from the sale of a money management unit investment banking 
revenue which includes merger advising and securities 
underwriting was down 27 percent 
cohen 43 had been under increasing pressure from american 
express to improve business some analysts speculated cohens 
departure stemmed from american express chairman james d robinson 
iiis desire to rein in the brokerage 
the fall was sudden for a man considered a wonderboy on wall 
