inc in 1971 and rose through the corporate ranks of the firm that 
became known as shearson hayden stone inc he was named chief 
executive officer in 1983 and chairman one year later 
cohen led shearsons expansion into investment banking in 1984 
with the acquisition of lehman brothers kuhn loeb he also was 
instrumental in the january 1988 acquisition of defunct brokerage 
ef hutton amp co for 962 million giving shearson a massive 
nationwide network of brokerage outlets 
but along with shearsons meteoric rise there were several 
notable embarrassments 
shearson lost the bidding war for rjr nabisco inc which was 
taken over last year for 25 billion by kohlberg kravis roberts amp 
co losing out on 200 million in fees in the process 
also shearsons reputation was sullied last year when a 
subsidiary boston co overstated its income when the firm had to 
write off about 100 million in bad investments in troubled texas 
bank mcorp and when it backed a hostile bid for pittsburghbased 
koppers co 
american express acquired shearson in 1981 for 360 million 
under the new stock offer shearson plans to sell 21 million 
shares of common stock for 12 a share directly to current 
shareholders american express would buy about 69 percent of the 
new stock and any shares not purchased 
american express would reduce its stake in shearson by offering 
shearson shares as a dividend to american express stockholders or a 
dividend in the form of 100 percent of a spinoff corporation 
formed with the shearson shares 
the old plan envisioned the sale of 20 million shares to the 
public 
