<TEXT>
changes in securities laws are being considered 
that would protect japanese companies from sneak attacks from 
corporate raiders but at the same time relax some restrictions on 
foreign investment finance ministry officials said wednesday 
the proposed legislation to be submitted to parliament when it 
reconvenes in march would go into effect by the years end they 
said 
a new 5 percent rule would require anyone whose holdings 
exceed 5 percent of a companys shares to report to the finance 
ministry stock exchanges and the company the officials said 
the new rule would make stock transactions more visible and 
prevent hostile raiders from collecting shares secretly said 
ministry spokesman tetsuo kabe 
last year american investor t boone pickens became the largest 
single shareholder in koito manufacturing co an auto parts maker 
when he obtained more than 20 percent of its shares mostly from a 
japanese stock speculator 
pickens has been trying unsuccessfully to gain representation on 
koitos board of directors 
experts said that the new legislation would make it more 
difficult for speculators to amass big holdings from a third party 
but the legislation also would ease restrictions on the tender 
offer bid a public announcement of intent to acquire at a fixed 
price any or all of a companys securities foreign investors have 
said the current rules are too strict and curb their investment in 
japan 
the ministry says there have been only three such bids in 19 
years 
such bids no longer would require 10 days advance notice to the 
ministry and investors would be allowed 60 days for bidding 
instead of the current 30 officials said 
japanese law now requires nonresidents to have agents in japan 
for such bids the new legislation would allow lawyers accountants 
and others in addition to banks and securities firms to represent 
nonresident investors 
we realized we have to eliminate restrictions such as advance 
notice because among the western countries only japan is imposing 
such requirements said another ministry official speaking on 
condition of anonymity we expect the revised law will encourage 
foreign investment in japan 
kabe said the 5 percent rules main purpose is to prevent wild 
fluctuations in share prices 
when an investor buys a large number of one companys shares it 
often causes wild price moves 
those who fail to report under the new legislation would be 
punished with fines or prison terms although details remain to be 
worked out kabe added 
at present the only reporting requirement is that companies 
issuing shares must notify the ministry of major changes in 
shareholders holding more than 10 percent of their shares he said 
critics said the revised law may not have much impact on the 
market because most stocks are permanently held by business 
partners and financial institutions including major securities and 
life insurance companies and banks 
financial institutions would be exempted from having to 
immediately notify the ministry as long as they did not intend to 
gain management rights by increasing their holdings to more than 5 
percent of a companys shares the ministry said 
</TEXT>
