a widely watched gauge of consumer confidence 
sank in january for the third straight month dropping to the 
lowest point since after the october 1987 stock market crash 
according to a survey released wednesday 
the conference board said its consumer confidence index tumbled 
to 1051 in january from 113 in december and 1158 in january a 
year earlier 
fabian linden executive director of the new yorkbased business 
research groups consumer research center said the size of the 
decline must be regarded as a possible though not unmistakable 
indication of economic troubles ahead 
he noted however that in the context of the surveys 
history the present level of consumer confidence does not yet 
signal a likely recession in the coming months 
the january reading was the lowest since the index registered 
1008 in november 1987 the month after world financial markets 
suffered major setbacks on oct 19 1987 the dow jones industrial 
average of 30 bluechip stocks plummeted 508 points to 173874 a 
loss of 226 percent of its value 
a monthly survey of 5000 households throughout the country 
indicated that people are less comfortable with their situations 
and less optimistic about the next six months than they were when 
polled in december the conference board said 
the latest poll showed 185 percent of all those responding 
expressed the view that business conditions were bad a slightly 
larger percentage than in december 
only about one in four respondents believed that jobs were 
plentiful a figure that has been going steadily lower in 
recent months on the employment outlook pessimists outnumbered 
optimists for the first time since late 1987 
expectations about economic conditions in the next halfyear 
have deteriorated the board said only 162 percent of the 
respondents thought that business would improve down about 2 
percentage points from december 
buying plans didnt show much change in the january survey the 
percentage of people planning to buy a car fell slightly to 69 
percent there still was strong interest in purchasing major 
appliances while the number of people planning to buy homes barely 
budged from its low level of 34 percent 
the survey is conducted for the board each month by national 
family opinion of toledo ohio 
