northwest airlines will spend 422 million over 
the next five years to lure customers with new plane interiors 
more choices of food and more ontime arrivals airline president 
fred malek said wednesday 
the nations fourthlargest airline already experimenting with 
german and thai dishes on some flights will spend about 100 
million to serve meals on more flights and add choices to standard 
inflight fare malek said 
northwest also will spend about 100 million to put more 
powerful engines on some boeing 747 jumbo jets strengthen 
maintenance capability and build up spare parts inventories to cut 
mechanical delays he said 
malek and chairman alfred checchi who with other investors 
acquired northwest last august for 37 billion have said they 
want it to be the first choice of travelers by 1995 
malek wouldnt detail how northwest rates in market surveys but 
said its performance is not too good 
the new management is working to boost employee morale said 
malek who was formerly president of marriott hotels and is 
cochairman of coldwell banker commercial group a leading real 
estate services company 
it is now time to couple this with some meaningful 
improvements in our levels of service he said 
malek predicted a consolidation of the airline industry and said 
northwest wants to take part either through acquisitions or joint 
ventures though he said it hasnt any immediate targets in sight 
besides improved meals maintenance capability and enticements 
such as free drinks and headsets for transatlantic passengers 
northwest will spend 80 million to refurbish its 324 planes malek 
said 
executive class passengers will have wider seats in the 
airlines boeing 747 jumbo jets window rows will still be two 
seats wide but center tiers will be three rather than four seats 
wide 
