<TEXT>
shearson lehman hutton inc took steps wednesday 
to bolster its financial footing under tighter control of parent 
american express co following the sudden resignation of shearson 
chairman peter a cohen 
the departure of cohen a cigarchomping wall street wunderkind 
typified the faltering fortunes of the nations secondlargest 
brokerage and of the securities industry which is mired in a 
protracted slump following the booming 1980s 
nine years after acquiring shearson american express removed 
the final highlevel link to the firms past when company chairman 
james d robinson iii asked cohen to leave amid mounting acrimony 
between the two executives 
american express and shearson on wednesday jointly announced a 
plan to raise about 250 million by offering stock to existing 
shareholders it replaces a public offering scrapped because of the 
firms slumping stock price and cohens resignation tuesday 
under the new plan american express would cut its stake in 
shearson to about 45 percent from 61 percent enabling it to drop 
the brokerage from its balance sheet american express would remain 
shearsons largest stakeholder 
a sign of tighter parental control came with the appointment of 
howard l clark jr chief financial officer and executive vice 
president of american express as shearsons new president and ceo 
clarks father was american express chairman before robinson 
clark said in a telephone interview that his shortterm goal 
is to get out and see the employees and management and retail 
system i will be doing a lot of that longer term is to restore 
shearson to its prior levels of returns 
he said his appointment would not mark a radical change in the 
relationship between american express and shearson analysts had a 
different view 
basically theyre running the company directly now said 
lawrence eckenfelder an analyst with prudentialbache securities 
inc robinson always had influence but it was peter cohens 
company 
shearsons current troubles stem in part from a recession on 
wall street stemming from a decline in individual stock activity 
mergers and acquisitions and securities underwriting because of 
their size and exposure in many areas nos 1 and 2 merrill lynch amp 
co and shearson have been among the hardest hit 
but analysts lay much of the blame on overexpansion shearson 
moved from a mediumsized retail outfit to a diversified brokerage 
by acquiring investment banking firm lehman brothers kuhn loeb in 
1984 and retail brokerage ef hutton amp co in 1988 
in this drive to become a major global fullservice firm 
they like merrill expanded to the point where they started to 
realize diminishing returns eckenfelder said they found out 
you can be all things to all people but you cant always make money 
doing it 
for cohen 43 described as a tough negotiator driven to 
transform shearson into a topflight firm the fall was swift 
last week he offered a hint of his own demise and of his soured 
relationship with robinson asked bluntly during a stockoffering 
presentation why he still had his job cohen said if robinson 
wants to punch my ticket he can 
he did american express officials say the company now will 
focus on assessing what problems need to be resolved they do not 
rule out a sharp consolidation following the 80s growth 
shearson will be adapting to the demands and requirements of 
the environment said lawrence armour an american express senior 
vice president shearson is really filled with talented 
highenergy people he said i dont think longrange planning 
strategic thinking is one of the things they shine at 
securities industry analysts said clark is the antithesis of the 
brash and combative cohen an investment banker in the 1970s 
clark who turns 46 on thursday was described as a subdued and 
practical manager expected to run shearson less aggressively than 
cohen 
over the next several years you could see a swing back to the 
shearson of old where the main concern was the retail side of the 
business said perrin long of lipper analytical services 
the first order of business is the new stock offer shearson 
plans to sell 21 million shares of common stock for 12 a share to 
current shareholders american express would buy about 69 percent 
of the new stock and any shares not purchased the old plan 
envisioned the sale of 20 million shares to the public 
shearson stock reacted positively to the developments rising 75 
cents to 12 in new york stock exchange trading wednesday after a 
75cent rise on tuesday spurred largely by cohens resignation 
american express would reduce its stake in shearson by awarding 
shearson shares to american express stockholders as a special 
dividend 
as it moves forward shearson still faces the expansion problems 
left behind by cohen including the merger with hutton the 
securities industrys largest ever 
analysts and american express officials say shearson paid too 
much for hutton 962 million when retail brokering was slumping 
after the stock market crash in 1987 
in addition shearson must patch up morale among its merged 
troops particularly its 10500 stockbrokers john feloni a former 
hutton executive who wrote a book about the merger said huttons 
trademark was that of a friendly retail brokerage while shearson 
symbolized the arrogance characterizing the 80s takeover craze 
it was just a culture clash said feloni who now runs his 
own small investment firm if there were better times i think 
they might have overcome all that now theres just no room for 
error 
