<TEXT>
a former official of lucky stores inc has 
settled civil insider trading charges that he tipped his father to 
the planned acquisition of the company federal regulators 
announced wednesday 
the securities and exchange commission said david hellberg 
agreed to the settlement without admitting or denying wrongdoing in 
documents filed tuesday at federal court in salt lake city 
hellberg a former manager of special projects for a subsidiary 
of dublin califbased lucky stores was fined 328844 but us 
district judge aldon anderson waived all but 5000 of the fine 
because hellberg was unable to pay more 
the penalty will take roughly half his net assets short of 
selling his house said james a kidney an sec attorney in 
washington 
the sec complaint charged that hellberg tipped his father 
gerald hellberg in 1988 to a planned acquisition of lucky by 
irvine califbased american stores co 
the father allegedly bought 15000 in call options for lucky 
common stock when american announced a 45ashare tender offer 
the father allegedly made more than 328000 in illegal profits 
kidney said the father has not settled with the sec and that the 
son has not made any agreement with the government to testify at 
his fathers upcoming trial 
the younger hellbergs lawyer doug griffith was in a 
conference late wednesday and was not immediately available for 
comment 
</TEXT>
