<TEXT>
northrop corp said it has agreed to sell the 
twin highrises that house its century city headquarters to reduce 
its 12 billion debt 
the builder of the b2 stealth bomber also said it would sell a 
53acre site in anaheim where 1300 employees produce missile test 
equipment and advanced sensors for aircraft helicopters and 
missiles 
northrop said the properties are being sold for a total of more 
than 250 million it did not break down figures but real estate 
experts previously said the 15 and 19story century city 
buildings with about 540000 square feet of space would bring 
about 220 million 
northrop will lease back its 131000squarefoot corporate 
offices in one of the century city buildings 
the employees in anaheim are being transferred to facilities in 
hawthorne and el segundo and will not be laid off although their 
division is undergoing a previously announced reduction of 500 
workers through attrition company spokeswoman maria oharenko said 
northrop said the sale of the office buildings is expected to be 
completed next month and the anaheim sale completed in 1991 
the california state teachers retirement system is buying the 
twin towers the anaheim property is being purchased by taiyo 
development usa torrance an american subsidiary of a japanese 
company 
northrops new chief executive kent kresa said earlier this 
month the company hopes to sharply reduce its debt in the 1990s and 
eliminate shortterm bank debt by the middle of the decade 
</TEXT>
